OE_upsetting: A code blue in the CCU where the patient was hemorrhaging from his mouth and nose. My attending and I weren’t able to intubate him because of the blood. The code team refused to stop chest compressions so we could have a better view. My shield and surgical mask fell into the field (I was still wearing an N95). ENT or trauma surgery is not currently responding to emergent surgical airway calls. After the code was called and the patient was pronounced dead I was covered in his blood. I had to rush back down to the OR because I got paged that a stroke code was coming in. The OR was busy the entire evening. I showered in the anesthesia showers (no soap, so I used chlorhexidine in my hair and on my body). No clean towels so I used paper towels. Shower is covered in grime and I didn’t have shower shoes - so I wore my home shoes in the shower. The following day I came home and cried. I then receive a phone call from a different attending in my department saying he would have done things differently, asked me why I didn’t attempt a surgical airway, and pimped me about the indications for a surgical airway. My first feeling was incompetence. I felt inadequate, ill equipped, unintelligent, and small. The best part was this attending didn’t call the attending I was with during the code to discuss management - he just called me. Not a single superior called me to make sure I was emotionally okay.
OE_positive: Appreciation for fresh air. My husband and I are both Anesthesia residents. We spend 12 hours straight under an N95 mask for six days straight. By the sixth day, when your body is sick of being hypercarbic, you just take tons of  NSAIDs to get through the day while battling the worst migraine of your life. The feeling of breathing fresh air is indescribable. Appreciation my family is safe and my husband is safe.
OE_other: All anesthesia residents and attendings should be given a p100 mask. Wearing an old N95 every single day all day long is not healthy.

OE_upsetting:
Overall I've seen a lot of resilience and people really being creative and motivated for change. Seeing the ED physician in NYC take her life was upsetting and makes me feel less secure about the future with colleagues having PTSD or resulting emotional challenges to work through. I worry we're not prepared as a country or health care system to be kind and care for these people who have been traumatized. The way NYC was pretty much left to fend for itself in such an under resourced fashion is also upsetting. 
The most upsetting things to me have been the US government response for our own preparedness but also our country's dismissive response to the global response of collaboration to the pandemic. Friends from around the world in large and small and low income/high income countries have been concerned about us. We should be leading and be an example. 
I also sense a tension in the academic sphere of people rushing to publish and study everything COVID which is important, but many of these people aren't front line workers. It seems exploitative or predatory, even within Yale. I'm also aware of some significant bullying of the academic side toward the front line clinicians at this time.
OE_positive: Seeing the creativity and team effort in so many spheres in the clinical setting and others in the community developing ways to help others.

young adult children home
I feel more secure having them in one place

OE_upsetting: reviewing written statements from people who are currently incarcerated about the conditions in prisons and jails during the COVID pandemic- and trying to respond with policy recommendations for the facility.
OE_positive: watching our section leadership rise to the challenge of the pandemic and demonstrate true creativity and compassion to problem-solve
OE_other: I feel very proud to be part of this community.

OE_upsetting: anxiety and fear from a possible exposure
OE_positive: The most positive was developing stronger bonds with co-workers.
OE_other: I think this has brought a more unified and strong community in our hospitals

OE_upsetting: Feeling isolated from my family, so sad
OE_positive: Appreciate and grateful for my freedom
OE_other:
Should have been advised sooner to wear masks during face to face contact with patients

OE_upsetting: Lack of interaction with people while working from home. It has been difficult to get in contact with manager and other staff members in order to do my job. I have felt as if the work load has increased with little recognition from management or a lack of support.
OE_positive: Spending more time with my spouse.
OE_other: Nursing staff is not being treated properly during this pandemic at YH. We were given more work, we are spending more time working, more responsibilities and were told by the University that we would not be getting raises this year but the staff in the union is. It is insulting and ridiculous to treat the nurses like that. We are working so hard to help with all the Covid work as well as the usual work and are getting no recognition or compensation for it. It is very upsetting.

OE_upsetting: My father in law was in the icu and died and we were not allowed to be with him due to covid restrictions, even though he didn’t have covid-19
OE_positive: Making follow up phone calls to patients with probable covid to make sure they were ok—they were very appreciative that I reached out to them.  Also, just that friends I haven’t heard from in a long time have contacted me to see how I was.
OE_other: I work in a clinic, not a hospital

OE_upsetting: I exhibited symptoms after a family gathering for my sons birthday. ( we practiced social distancing and face covering).  I tested negative, but felt very guilty
OE_positive: Spent more time with my Elven year old son and my husband.

OE_upsetting:
Having had exposure to someone that became positive and not being informed directly (I had to ask myself). I had SOB for a week or 2 and didn’t get tested because of lack of fever (this was in early March). 

I felt nothing would be done unless I was severely ill, which made me concerned, scared and hopeless. As someone who had severe asthma growing up and who survived varicella PNA at 20 years of age, I know what it feels like to not be able to breath, be at the brink of getting intubated while seeing your parents in tears and being isolated in a SDU room for 2 weeks. 

I worried for myself, I am alone here, but also for my parents. Who would help them if I’m sick or gone? Would they fly up here from FL? That’s dangerous too! On top of that having to hide your fear and be strong for them also took a toll. And then you think about your patients. What if I DO have this... I’m still going to work, it’s highly contagious, etc. 

Overall it’s been OK, most days are good. There’s always something to be grateful for and optimistic about, it’s helped me grow and improve on skills... but it’s been exhausting.
OE_positive:
Several things, can’t name one!: My dad fell ill (SOB, desats, fever), but improved and is back to normal. Got back in touch with med school friends I hadn’t talked to in years. Received masks from a total stranger. Saw all the love and support that the majority of people have for one another.  

It makes me feel hopeful, optimistic, that there’s more good people than not, and that when society unites, and works as one towards a common goal, beautiful things happen. Look at NYC, look at YNHH... amongst all deaths and horrible things, we have stories of love and support, and we’ve flattened the curve. We just have to put our minds and souls to it and think about how our actions affect others. It makes me feel we will get through this.
OE_other: I’m very proud to see how specialties have left their “unspoken differences” aside and are working together to fight this pandemic. I hope we can continue this sense of collegiality across the hospital once we return to a new “normal”, and that we all come out stronger and wiser.

OE_upsetting: Watching my neighbor being taken away in the ambulance with EMS in full PPE gear. A week later, my neighbor passed away in the hospital.  The thought of him dying alone and now watching his wife and children suffer is extremely upsetting.
OE_positive: Spending more quality time with my family.  Spring is generally the busiest time of the year as my children play sports (13 and 16 years old). Though it is upsetting that their seasons have been cancelled, it has afforded us more time as a family.  We have been able to eat meals together and are not at the mercy of an overcommitted schedule.

OE_upsetting: I can't say I have been very upset about anything aside from the news I hear about hate crimes, especially against asians. Also, my neighbors are not observing social distancing (friends of children coming over to play bastketball every other day)
OE_positive: parents shipping PPE to me from abroad. being able to spend more time with my daughter and husband at home. having a nanny who is willing to work with us through covid. card games via zoom with friends
OE_other: Even though it is not necessary, seeing that people recognize the hard work of healthcare workers is encouraging. Also, getting notifications on numbers, transparency about the numbers of pt discharges has been really nice.

OE_upsetting: Lack of support for parents trying to deal with home schooling children.  There is so much focus on re-opening businesses but no focus on opening schools.  I don't see how a hairdresser is more essential than the education of children.  No one is going to be able to go to work if their children need to stay home and day cares aren't open.  It doesn't make sense, and there are no support systems in the hospital for working parents to try to help educate their children.  The last thing I want to do when I get home from work is force and fight with my child to do their work.
OE_positive: Not having essential businesses open, and social distancing has made it so that when I am not at work, I can focus on just being home and relaxing and not having juggle extracurricular activities, birthday day parties, family parties, etc.  My husband, daughter and I are able to just stay home, relax and be with each other.  My husband has found a new love for cooking which has been a huge weight off my shoulders.

OE_upsetting: Inappropriate, rude people telling me "that I don't know what I am doing" when I am doing what is required to keep people safe. I felt extremely upset by the event , yet was extremely gratified by the support that the security guard gave to me.
OE_positive: The camaraderie experienced with other staff that I knew before, but have really gotten to know them through this. The random acts of kindness that I see people doing for each other.

OE_upsetting: People not taking it seriously and not taking proper precautions, thus putting others in danger
OE_positive: My co fellows covering in hospital clinical duties as I am pregnant.

OE_upsetting: Realizing that policies were based on supply over logic.  Realizing that the hospital administration does not really care for its workers. All the signs of "health care heroes" are more of a bandaid of nice empty words, and a lack of action.
OE_positive: I always knew I could rely on my co-residents and the pandemic just showed that even more. OE_other: This pandemic exposed the several flaws in the American health care system. Things need to change. No new normal. We need to revamp and change our practice.

OE_upsetting: No answer
OE_positive: Idea of finishing residency gives me a great deal of pleasure

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting part is the lack of federal response or realistic plan, and this makes me feel hopeless like we will never solve this problem as a society, and that the vulnerable will pay the highest price.
OE_positive: Supporting my kids, and having a loving partner makes all the difference.  getting more time with them is the most positive.
OE_other: Thank you for caring about this.

OE_upsetting: I was presumed Covid + early in March, along with several of my co-workers. At that time, testing was not available, when it became available it was already 2 weeks into my illness and the results would have taken too long to get back to me. I have a multigenerational household, three members are at an age related risk with co-factors such as asthma, hypertension and age >90/dementia. The idea that anyone could also be infected and, we could become gravely ill, acquire a permanent disability, or death frightened me. Opening up work too soon, or asking medical staff to come back in, while symptomatic (ie coughing) is disgraceful. These things keep me awake at night.
OE_positive: being allowed to work from home has been a mental god-send. The time spent together is has been a comforting, knowing my co-workers are all safe at home has as well.
OE_other: I think hospital policy towards patients, is also absolutely reflective in the care and protection of its workers. It will be a disservice to ask staff to return back to work while exhibiting ANY symptoms.

OE_upsetting: Co-workers being diagnosed Covid positive. I felt very vulnerable, as I work in the same environment they do.
OE_positive: Having the occasional ability to work from home. At home, I feel safe and can control my environment. At work, I am often called into the clinical area, where I feel more vulnerable.
OE_other: Management is pulled to managing the crisis and away from their staff. Staff are left to manage themselves. Sometimes, this adds to the feeling of isolation.

OE_upsetting: People distrusting others and me on the sidewalks/elevators. Made me feel like I didn’t belong or wasn’t supposed to be there

OE_upsetting:
Because of age>65, I was told that I could no longer provide direct patient care. This also ended bedside teaching of house staff and nurses. I identify as a clinician and educator and this change of role has been a challenge. 
I am anxious about the possibility of not resuming that role. I can retire but am not ready to retire. I believe that I still have a great deal to contribute to patients and trainees.
OE_positive: Witnessing the team work and camaraderie. It is wonderful to see people pulling together (mostly). It reminds me of my time in the military when there were shared experiences, a common enemy and a coming together to overcome adversity.

OE_upsetting: I became sick with symptoms cw covid-19.  I tested negative twice during that time, yet had a cxr with bilateral infiltrates.  I recently learned that I have antibodies.  I have a history of pneumonia so was very concerned about my personal health when sick, not helped by what seems to have been false negative tests.  also worried about exposing family members and making them ill. near-impossible to self-isolate at home.
OE_positive: Our staff have come together as a team. Also, the support for medical workers shown by the community has been absolutely unbelievable.  Finally feel appreciated as a healthcare worker.

OE_upsetting: It's irritating, that they will cut physician hours or other hours, because of finances. Just because volumes are low, doesn't mean the work isn't 2-3xs more demanding and exhausting. At one site, I feel exhausted and understaffed often. I've mentioned my concerns many times about it, but at the end of the day, it's the suits who make the decisions. Also, I feel like at times, some providers don't always pull their weight the same, and it's irritating.
OE_positive: Patients have been unbelievably grateful. I'm exhausted and burned out in an over-worked type way. But the renewed respect with the doctor-patient interaction has really helped my burnout. No one does this job for a "thank you" but we certainly never did it to be treated poorly. So I think a new respect for what we do, both inside and outside of a pandemic, has been incredibly helpful. We often feel overlooked and dismissed in the ER.
OE_other: I felt overburdened by the emails I'd get daily, if not hourly at first, it always seemed to be contradicting. I'm still annoyed at the understaffing at one hospital site. But overall, feel grateful for my health and job. And to play such an important role. I just wish we would've had the opportunity to test people even earlier, because I'm sure I was seeing COVID even weeks before we were "allowed" to test.

OE_upsetting: Cancelling a trip I had been looking forward to for months. Felt sad to not see a friend and be isolated from other family and friends.
OE_positive: Seeing the outpouring of support for health care workers from the community in New Haven. Being thanked by families over the phone for the work that I am doing with a new sense of appreciation and respect.

OE_upsetting: deaths of people close to friends and family.  luckily nobody in my family but it has been very hard to deal with so much death.

I felt like we were really prepared for disaster and luckily to date we haven't had dire situation. OE_other: it seems like everyone has everyone else's backs.  That has been very comforting to me when treating COVID patients.  Like someone's there to help me and ensure my safety.

OE_upsetting:
Since I cannot go in to the hospital, feeling like a non-doctor - I went into this field to help people but am immunocompromised -- so I am basically useless at my regular job. 
 Feeling like my specialty (pediatrics) and my subspecialty even within pediatrics doesn't matter at all right now; feeling like the only thing that actually really counts is keeping people alive.

OE_upsetting: I was removed from direct clinical care because I have diabetes (despite excellent personal control) and my program director made the executive decision that I should not be on the front lines because I was "high risk". I was not involved much with this decision, there was no conversation about data that supported or refuted this decision or reevaluating this decision once more data was available, and there was no plan made for when I would reenter clinical care. Furthermore, residents at my hospital were only given roles on covid-positive floors which left no opportunity for me to participate in non-covid care. It was unclear how this would effect my education. I was offered no emotional support or opportunity to debrief from any leadership in my program. This left me with a huge crisis of purpose and role, loneliness, and existential angst. I feel isolated and devalued and discriminated.
OE_positive: For the first time in my residency training I've had the time to reflect on the meaning of my job of being a resident and what I value about it. I've had more time for family as well. And plenty of time to eat well and exercise which I don't usually have during covid. These self care techniques allow me to appreciate the role of resident and trainee in a way I found hard when I felt our work hours were too demanding.
OE_other: Not having a voice in where we get placed and not knowing what is coming next are sources of high levels of distress

OE_positive: Society has been appreciative. Many companies are offering free and discounts for healthcare workers, or even just saying thank you. Precovid, health care workers were not recognized

OE_upsetting: Anxiety about workforce shortages and subsequently not being able to come home to my family.
OE_positive: Outpouring of support from friends, frequent check ins, providing humor - improved emotional wellbeing

OE_upsetting: At times it felt that PPE policy was made based on availability by administrators who have never cared directly for COVID-19 patients with little concern for the frontline providers.
OE_positive: Optimistic that we may be leveling off cases
OE_other: It definitely feels like ICU and ED physicians are shouldering the brunt of the load

OE_upsetting: Being told by co-residents that they experienced cleaning supplies and PPE being withheld from them early on. Isolation and a loss of sense of purpose as things are changing so rapidly at the hospital.

OE_positive: My family and friends have been checking in on me frequently, it feels great to be connected
OE_other: This pandemic exposed so much systemic and structural issues in our hospitals, healthcare system, education, society, domestic and foreign policies, in the global economic-political structures, it exposed so much lack of care/competence all around that I really hope we can take those lessons and act on them, not just forget once things normalize and allow business as usual.

OE_upsetting: Court closure delaying divorce.
OE_positive: Zoom meetings with colleagues and friends.
OE_other: Much harder logistically (restricted entrances, angry parents who can't visit, anxious parents, anxious staff, confusing and constant changing and updating of protocols, having to wear masks all day, concern about pay, childcare, and staffing. Considerable increase in administrative time and planning. Harder to get appropriate follow up.  Concern that federal or even state recommendations aren't optimal for me locally based on our curve or timing in pandemic.

OE_upsetting: My father has stage 4 cancer and I am unable to spend time with him because of the risk of spreading COVID-19 to him.  The risk of passing COVID-19 to him causes extreme anxiety and fear.
OE_positive: Learned which co-workers I can count on

OE_upsetting: Catching the covid virus, and not being aware of where I had a breach of PPE. I am usually very careful about my precautions. Also, there is a lot of worry about being in quarantine away from my kids
OE_positive: Seeing the team work and courageous work of staff at the hospital.

OE_upsetting: Been yelled at unfairly by supervisors for asking questions
OE_positive: Spending more time with my family has been great. I love being with my kids more.

OE_upsetting: Worry about bringing the virus home.  My husband is older than me and I would hate for him to get sick.  Also worry about my elderly mother who lives in an Independent Senior community.
OE_positive: I so appreciate where I live.  There are beautiful walks that are not crowded and wonderful neighbors available to help if needed.
OE_other: I am working one day a week on an inpatient unit to help out.  Meeting new people and spending a lot of time learning the medical content for the medical care provided.  Overall it has been a great experience despite the stress of the virus and going into the hospital.

OE_upsetting: Rescheduling my wedding. Initially felt traumatic and like I suffered a huge loss. Then came to terms with it and focused more on appreciating the importance of people's health and safety.
OE_positive: Becoming closer with coworkers through shared difficult work experiences. I worked on an adult covid unit which was also a CMO unit and the relationships formed with co-residents, nurses and attendings were invaluable and irreplaceable.
OE_other: It is hard to work in the hospital when it is still so busy with COVID and to hear on the news about states reopening when it doesn't feel like it should be happening. It makes me fearful of the current state of the hospital continuing this way and needing to work on an adult unit again. Hearing the national government's response has made me feel angry and powerless.

OE_upsetting: Watching my 8 year old son struggle with his anxiety around it.
OE_positive: Being around and talking to my colleagues.

OE_upsetting: My peers, who are pediatric residents, are caring for CMO patients, and we are not accustomed to frequently managing dying patients. It makes me feel anxious for their well being and scared to work on that unit next week. I’m worried about being emotional overwhelmed.
OE_positive: We have really come together to take care of our patients, I am so comforted to know we all have each others’ backs.

OE_upsetting: That individuals would take it more seriously.  Because we work in healthcare, we're aware of the precautions we need to take and unfortunately, the danger this pandemic can erupt to.  The regular person does not understand the real ramifications this can have on them or their family members.  I find that frustrating.  Also, I have a high school sophomore that has been distance learning since March.  She is also a scholar athlete who will be unable to play the sport that she loves due to this pandemic.  She misses her friends (they all participate on zoom, yet it's not the same) and she's upset that she'll be unable to play the sport that she loves.  This is not just heartbreaking for her, it is also heartbreaking for us because as parents, we just don't have the answers for her.  With that said, this basically is a first for all of us.  All of our lives have changed due to this and it seems, going forward, we're all going to have to adjust to the new "normal".  There is no doubt that we will get through it together.  Stay safe, healthy and be well
OE_positive: That my family is all together.  We aren't rushing around and are able to even sit at the dinner table and talk for a while.  Besides the fact that I'm getting sick and tired of cooking every night.  I love having them right there.
OE_other: Dr. Genecin, his Sr. Leadership Team and their administrative staff have been exceptional in communicating with all of the Yale Health Staff.  I think our Senior Leadership at Yale Health has been extremely forthcoming with information that they've received and express it to all in numerous emails on a weekly basis.  Dr. Genecin, and his Sr. Team have had numerous virtual town halls with all staff communicating the present and next steps and they've all been so open with answering questions from the staff.  They have been very diligent in making sure that all of the Yale Health staff and our patients, have been kept safe and informed of every step of the way.  They all should be commended for the work that they have done and continue to do.

OE_upsetting: when 2 of my covid patients on my census died, and 3 others died on the floor in the same day.
OE_positive: camaraderie amongst the yale resident physicians, attending physicians, pediatrics program leadership, and pediatric nursing staff

OE_upsetting: Husband - healthcare worker - was deployed to COVID floor and has been working there.  Enrolled in research study and found to have COVID antibodies.  He was asymptomatic.
OE_positive: Spending lots of time with my children and husband since we are quarantined.  Trying to stay positive during this difficult time. We have remained healthy and this makes me grateful

OE_upsetting: Not being able to see family as much.
OE_positive: Comradery
OE_other: N/A

OE_upsetting: Being displaced from my outpatient position has been very upsetting, essentially being laid off from your job while still being employed.  Having to scavenge hours within different departments to secure enough hours to cover my 40 hrs/wk, and not knowing when outpatient clinics will open is very distressing.
OE_positive: Seeing the outpouring of support from the community for my colleagues has been very heartening.
OE_other: I think one of the hardest parts about this time as a healthcare worker is that while those on the frontline are inundated with covid 19 patients, there is an entire aspect of the hospital workforce that has been displaced.

OE_upsetting: Working as the only fellow in our group the hospital the first few weeks of the major changes. Worked a lot of hours with lot of unknowns. The press was also in full "doom and gloom" force at that time.
OE_positive: Being able to spend a lot of time with my wife and dog. They are great to be around.

OE_upsetting: Trying to deal with those outside of the hospital (friends, family) who truly believe that this entire response to COVID is being overblown.

Patient families not being present with patient for surgery. I felt like the patients do not have the support they need--and I did not feel as connected with patient and families. Also I was upset over colleagues getting sick---although the testing has been negative.
OE_positive: Two of our children moved home. While stressful at time, it have been wonderful being with them.

OE_upsetting:
The most upsetting aspect of the COVID-19 pandemic for me has been the visitor restriction policies implemented at the hospitals.  One of the new voluntary roles I have undertaken is calling MICU patients' families to give support and basic medical updates as they are not allowed to be with the admitted family member, many of which are intubated.  It is heartbreaking to speak with some of these families. They are very thankful and appreciative of the care, but want to be at the bedside and provide emotional support to the sick family member.  I can only do so much over the phone.  This is not just the case in the hospital, but for those patients that die, family members cannot even be present then and funerals have changed so much.  Loved ones oftentimes cannot even see the deceased.
Also, while patients are getting outstanding care by all staff, it is good for an advocate to be at bedside, asking questions and getting the most up to date information and to ensure that no errors in aspects of care are made.
This lack of visitation makes me feel awful and helpless and while I understand why the policies are implemented, I feel the stress level for families for having a loved one in the hospital is much higher than during "normal" times.
OE_positive: Just seeing the trend of cases and hospitalizations in the northeast USA leveling out and downtrending is reassuring.  It makes me hopeful that while the end may not totally be in sight, we are headed in the right direction.  While this is good news, I am also hesitant in my optimism such as relaxing of restrictions and social distancing and opening of commercial businesses and such will lead to an uptick in cases and a return to what has been.

OE_upsetting: Nothing. My biggest issue is the conflict of feeling like I am not doing enough to help with the pandemic but also relief that I haven't been called to do more because I would risk infecting my (otherwise healthy) family.

seeing others not believe the seriousness of this impending pandemic, and the failure of preparation and of a coordinated response/plan (particularly of the federal government, but also the initial hospital response e.g. the switch from no masks to maybe masks to yes everyone mask, which was ultimately the right decision).
OE_positive: colleagues and friends from the past reaching out; the amazing progress of science/research; the resilience and generosity of essential workers and healthcare workers in dealing with an incredibly stressful, overwhelming and potentially dangerous situation of unknown duration.

OE_upsetting: not being able to work
OE_positive: occassional visits with my significant other to cook dinner together and spend an evening together

OE_upsetting: 5 patients dying in one day on our floor, and feeling like since my interns had carried them and the nurses treated them, I was the only one not having to deal directly with the death. Felt guilty.
OE_positive: Seeing what the fantastic people around me can accomplish
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Taking care of CMO/end of life adult COVID patients as a pediatric provider and watching them die alone without family members physically with them in the room
OE_positive: Watching everyone set up to help during this time and the thanks and praise myself and my colleagues have received as healthcare providers
OE_other: None

OE_upsetting: seeing those on the front lines of healthcare put themselves and family at risk
OE_positive: more time with kids at home
OE_other: having kids at home but equal work demands has been the most difficult part, for me personally

OE_upsetting: limited elective surgery
OE_positive: Connecting with old friends

OE_upsetting: Unable to socialize with others
OE_positive: Fewer work hours

OE_upsetting: Feeling unappreciated by your team & worrying about bringing something home with me that could potentially put my family in harms way.
OE_positive: Seeing how my family has become closer.

OE_upsetting: Having to go into work every day while my husband and kids are home. I feel like I’m missing out on family time especially unable to evaluate my kids for feelings of depression because I’m not home enough
OE_positive: Gas prices decreasing and less traffic. It makes me feel happy
OE_other: No thank you

OE_upsetting: I was pulled to work on a COVID inpatient unit. I was supposed to be getting training on the inpatient unit, but instead I felt like the charge nurse of that unit was rushing me to get my own assignment and I was already uncomfortable in such an unfamiliar environment. I've never worked on a medicine inpatient unit and I've never experienced dealing with patients dying. Aside from dealing with the stress of that charge nurse and an unfamiliar environment, I was having a panic attack after having to wear an N95 mask for long period of time. So I ended up having to leave and got reassigned to a non-COVID unit. Once I left that unit that day, I remember crying and being completely out of it. I went to my car and then I had to call my therapist and do an emergency phone session with him because I was losing my mind with the mix of being thrown onto a unit with situations I've never worked around in my entire life and being uncomfortable with not being able to breathe.
OE_positive: The most positive thing that has happened was being able to get my mental health under control and being able to work in an environment that is suitable for me.
OE_other: n/a

OE_upsetting: Had to quarantine, had to be tested, had to home school young children, change work hours, increase workload
OE_positive: Public outreach and recognition

OE_upsetting: One of my most loved patients died
OE_positive: Less travel, closer to my family
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Feeling of getting exposure and feeling that my kids will get an infection from me as i am the only one working outside and rest family members works from home and  nobody os leaving house but as health care worker we need to work. It's our job.
OE_positive: Family support. And getting PPE.

OE_upsetting: Seeing private surgeons I previously worked with continue to operate despite the known danger
OE_positive: Being with family, working on my home

OE_upsetting: Seeing COVID-19 patients alone and helpless in the ICU with providers looking in on them in fear.
OE_positive: Spending time with my dog and family

OE_upsetting: Quarantine while sick by myself
OE_positive: Recognition from the town residents
OE_other: Panic attack after being sick and having to go back to work

OE_upsetting: People protesting stay home orders and not taking this pandemic seriously.
OE_positive: People being appreciative and expressing thanks to healthcare workers. It helps to feel that the daily illness and death that we are confronted with is appreciated and recognized.
OE_other: I honestly wish that there could be a window into what us medical providers do on a daily basis during this pandemic with the idea that people can see that this is a serious issue and we are risking our own health and lives to take cases of those who are ill. I think the biggest frustrations are those who are minimizing this illness and the terrible response by the president and federal government.

OE_upsetting:
I lost a close family member (motor vehicle accident) who was also a nurse (not in my hospital system) so it has been very upsetting not being able to mourn the loss of a young beautiful soul with my family.  
With regard to most upsetting part of working with COVID-19 patients, I cannot get the image of my young son (4 years old) running towards me to hug me after coming home from my shift when the pandemic first hit my hospital.  I yelled at him to stay away and my husband had to run and grab him.  The look of sheer confusion and disappointment on his face has stayed with me all of these weeks.  I cannot get that image out of my head.  He now understands I need to shower before hugging him.
OE_positive:
Seeing the outpouring of support from the community has been amazing.  I am typically a school nurse who only works per diem in labor and delivery (typically one weekend a month and summers).  I have been working exponentially more shifts since March.  On several occasions, colleagues from my school job and community have sent food, cookies, and other goodies. This makes us feel appreciated.  

I also have been thanked countlessly by the patients I have worked with over the past few months.  My Covid patients have been so appreciative of all we are doing to help them.

OE_upsetting: Unable to fit test a N-95 mask initially. I was very scared that I will either get exposed to COVID-19 or will not be able to see patients
OE_positive: Family/friends calling and checking on my well being
OE_other: use of tele-health to communicate is going to be a new norm

OE_upsetting: can't answer
OE_positive: I've seen many people go out of their way to do good things for others. Whether it's someone dropping off food or masks to an elderly neighbor  Or coworkers crying with each other after a difficult day. There's so many feelings and so many emotions and we are all experiencing them together.
OE_other: I can't wait for this all to be over but for humanity to not forget  How precious every little thing is.

OE_upsetting: inability to see family
OE_positive: had 2 IRB protocols accepted

OE_upsetting: Feeling the Pressure to intervene in a COVID patient whose condition is deteriorating though there are no reliable indicators to base the intervention upon...we’re just guessing
OE_positive: Feeling like I am contributing to the overall effort and lightening my colleagues workload, even a little bit
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Not able to attending important family reunions. Having important life events delayed or potentially cancelled.
OE_positive: Spending more time with live-in significant other.
OE_other: None.

OE_upsetting: My kids are out of daycare (it is closed) and my husband shoulders all the responsibility at home. Every day I am obligated to work is stressful and makes me anxious. My mind cannot be present on the task at hand at times because of the added stress at home.

This is petty but having my clinical decision making and that of the attending questioned by a transporter. A patient was diagnosed with covid outpatient and therefore we didn’t waste a test in our facility for the sake of preserving resources. The patient was admitted to a covid unit and the transporter was questioning whether or not the patient should go there because she didn’t see a positive result in the chart. Why she could see the chart was beyond me. The patient had covid, her admitting diagnosis was covid. Bring her upstairs so they can take care of her. This pandemic, while I don’t feel mentally distressed, has definitely put me more on edge and has me reacting more strongly to minor inconveniences.
OE_positive: Nothing comes to mind. This is monotonous and boring. I miss actually having to think about what might be wrong with my patients.
OE_other: It’s boring and I’m frustrated. Gowning up to enter my patient rooms is exhausting. Assuming everyone is infected is exhausting. I haven’t had a single patient with anything interesting in months and I work in the ER in an inner city. Everything is supposed to be interesting there. That’s why I got into emergency medicine. It doesn’t help that emergency medicine will never be the same. We’re sending people home that otherwise would’ve gotten million dollar workups because the risk of working them up in a densely covid populated facility is greater than the risks of whatever they might have. I’m exhausted and I’m done. Invent a vaccine guys.

OE_upsetting: Being told a patient that I was called to care for was not suspected to have COVID but then finding out that immediately after the interaction a decision was made to test the patient and he was positive.  It made me feel like no one was in control.
OE_positive: I very much appreciate all of the outpouring of recognition for my work (honor hour, billboards, signs, etc.)  I am simply doing what I do, but it is good to know that people now have a greater understanding of the work I do.
OE_other: I am very curious to see what changes that have been made in response to the pandemic stick once we return to "normal".  My hope is that we will realize that a lot of the pressure we typically feel from unnecessary regulations and bureaucracy is indeed unnecessary.

OE_upsetting: Not allowing visitors and using face time for family members to say good by. At least we could do that but was still hard
OE_positive: How everyone came together and is united and everyday comes to work and it makes you feel stronger
OE_other: Not at this time

OE_upsetting: Watching adult Covid patients on comfort measures only die alone without family or spiritual support
OE_positive: The way staff have worked together and supported each other and the positive regard for healthcare workers coming from the community and the gratitude expressed by people for work we do every day as part of our daily lives.
OE_other: Crazy, weird times, never expected to experience something like this in my career.

OE_upsetting:
Trip to Europe to see family was canceled.
Felt frustrated and angry at times
OE_positive:
Two children relocated back home during COVID
This made me very happy
OE_other:
I feel challenged by changes in my job responsibilities 
I appreciate the generosity of people doing good for others

OE_upsetting: People refusing to wear masks in public when I'm in the market, or yelling at others about their "personal liberties" online or in person while refusing to comply with the mandatory mask order. Seeing people I know act under the influence of online conspiracy theories and memes from far right ideology is deeply upsetting.
OE_positive: I ride the Peloton 5 or more days a week. It has given me a physical and emotional release, and I can work out with family members and friends remotely. It's a great tool I purchased last year, unrelated to the pandemic, but has become indispensable to me.
OE_other: I fear being exposed to other workers or patients who may be asymptomatic carriers. We only are given surgical masks for routine interaction, but physician should be wearing N95 full time for all clinical interactions. I can't get an N95 unless a surgical patient is Known COVID+, and the tests have a reportedly high false negative rate. It is of real concern to me. Also, there is seemingly no plan to test faculty and staff to help with getting offices and OR's open again. We need better PPE supplies and need more testing. There just doesn't seem to be any single cohesive plan and it is really frustrating.

OE_upsetting: Fear of not knowing what’s ahead.
OE_positive: Everyone coming together for one cause. The support from my family and my colleagues, and my friends.
OE_other: All of the negative media coverage about PPE is something we have not experienced within our system. I would not want to be anywhere else, than with my Baylor family.

OE_upsetting: There was a day in which I supervised residents who had to pronounce death five times in 3 hours. It was a lot, and there were a lot of tears from them for understandable reasons.  But what was hard was that I then had to go join planning zoom calls in which no one has a transparent plan.  And I had to go home to take care of my three kids.  there is no room for some of us to process this, because no one will help us find time in our lives to process it.
OE_positive: I've been so proud of my team of doctors mostly -- they are doing such great work and have been so selfless.
OE_other: I think its so hard for us to see this as a team sport -- and some times it hasn't felt that way.  I have felt very isolated or judged, but also notice that I am judging.

OE_upsetting: Taking care of my coworkers that got sick is difficult. Also, at the peak coming in everyday to multiple people getting intubated.
OE_positive: The outpouring of support from the community and families. Makes you feels recognized!
OE_other: I feel like we should have a stock pile of PPE for situations just like this. I don’t like the reissuing of used PPE or having to reuse my n95 but at least I have a mask which is more then some RNs in other hospitals. Overall, I feel like our hospital system is doing great reallocating resources and supporting us.

OE_upsetting: I haven't been able to spend time with my family because they have higher risk of getting seriously ill due to medical history and current health factors. This has been difficult for me to handle because we usually spend a good deal of time together.
OE_positive: My mother was able to isolate at her sister's house and has stayed safe and not had to be alone or in an unsafe environment. I was worried about her being at my brother's house because he has not taken this issue seriously and I thought he would put our mother at a greater risk than was necessary. I have been pleased that she was able to be with her sister for the past several weeks.
OE_other: No, I've said enough.

OE_upsetting: Mother diagnosed with COVID and not being able to be close by. Not being able to be physically close to loved ones
OE_positive:
Reconnecting with old friends.
Community members delivering free masks and food in appreciation
OE_other: The most stressful part has been the uncertainty - changes in hospital rules as well as uncertainty in the diagnosis and associated symptoms and feeling helpless in my medical knowledge base to comfort patients

OE_upsetting: Change in work assignments
OE_positive: Able to get other academic work completed

OE_upsetting: Feeling to pick between going to work as a healthcare provider and mother-- currently 35 weeks pregnant with two other small children at home and husband who also has high risk healthcare job; feeling increasingly anxious
OE_positive: allowed to slow down and spend more time as core family

OE_upsetting: Difficulty caring for a school-age child at home and performing my job responsibilities
OE_positive: I was able to complete more projects around my house and yard, including planting a garden. This provided a small sense of accomplishment
OE_other: I do not work directly in the hospital, but I have been providing care to patients in my outpatient office during this time

OE_upsetting:
nothing personally upsetting. I am annoyed by the young people in my town (and others) who are not appropriately social distancing.
I have also withdrawn personally into more movies/tv shows and audiobooks, avoiding contact with my family. this is a known stress reaction for me, but it bothers me that I pull away from my family and i feel angry with myself about it though understand its need as well for self preservation. I recognize this and am currently working to find a better balance.
OE_positive: I have been sleeping more and have more time with my family.  The interactions with the kids were stressful at first, but after we found a new schedule it is pleasant to see them in the afternoon, especially as the weather improves, and be able to do activities with them that I typically am not able to (as my work schedule is currently lighter than usual).
OE_other: I truly appreciate the front line workers directly taking care of patients and the administrators who are actively engaged in directing and managing the response, they are doing a tremendous job.

OE_upsetting: The most difficult thing is to manage child-care, home-schooling with continued work (on service and managing telehealth clinics) - it is difficult to be successful in all these domains with little support.
OE_positive: I have spent a great deal more time with my family and more time doing things I enjoy (cooking, working in yard and reading).
OE_other: My hospital was quickly responsive to managing operational needs during the pandemic

OE_upsetting: Due to my age and household medical issues, I no longer do face to face patient care, and I do not anticipate returning to FtoF patient care until there is an effective vaccine or very effective treatment for early onset infection. This is a major career change. On the other hand, I had been aware that I was past "retirement age" prior to the pandemic.
OE_positive: nothing to say.
OE_other: I have not been within the hospital walls since the pandemic was recognized. Some of my anwers about hospital climate are irrelevant, but there was no "no opinion" option.

OE_upsetting: The way this has affected my family; my husband is high risk we are adhering to strict isolation. My daughter is a nurse in NYC and I worry about her safety. My other daughter is unemployed in Boston.
OE_positive: Caring for my lactation mom's and newborns. They are so grateful for the care they received. Makes me feel good to have a positive impact on the beginning of their newborn's life/family during such a stressful time in general and with Covid-19 especially.
OE_other: I work in an outpatient ambulatory care setting so not as stressful as the hospital. I think about my nurse collogues there often as they have it much worse than me.

OE_upsetting: I consulted on a patient in his 60s with a new diagnosis of leukemia and COVID infection. Unfortunately he was not doing well and decided not to pursue any treatment. He had a son with special needs who also tested positive for COVID which limited his family's ability to visit at the end of his life. This was emotionally challenging and I felt sad and helpless at times.
OE_positive: I have been amazed by the teamwork approach to these uncertain times. I had an attending physician reach out by email to thank me and our team for our work even though he was the one on the frontlines caring for COVID patients. This made me feel proud and appreciated.

OE_upsetting: The way YNHHS is treating my wife and other frontline workers.  She works in an ambulatory practice that has not shut down.  She has been using the same N95 mask for 2 months now and has been buying her own PPE as they cannot provide it.
OE_positive: That I still have a job
OE_other: There is a major loss in the top down approach.  Major decisions are made from the top and by the time they hit the bottom things are a mess and not followed through on.

OE_upsetting: I feel unsupported by my department at work and feel pressure to take on more responsibility without the support or understanding of how this will impact my own health or wellness.
Isolation from my family to protect them from transmitting illness - makes me feel like I do not have the support system I need in place.
OE_positive: ability to connect with distant friends through different online platforms

OE_upsetting:
not being able to give investigational drugs to patients. 
Finding out that the research laboratories will open before clinical trials open
sounds like we care more about mice than people
OE_positive: telemedicne

OE_upsetting: Not being able to be with my co-residents before residency is over and we all move away from each other.
OE_positive: My work hours being cut back allowed me to take care of personal things that needed attention .
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Living in trailer parked in my driveway because I have a son on a ventilator; cannot take chance of him being infected.  Big pain in the ass plus expense.
OE_positive: Riding my motorcycle on my days off; working in my yard. My motorcycle is my salvation right now, with my hot wife of 31 years!!
OE_other: =Its been a challenge, but Im doing alright.

OE_upsetting: Going through a very difficult transition in my life and not being able to be with my primary support team due to social distancing.
OE_positive: Support from society, work, and family/friends in regards to being a nurse and working with Covid patients.
OE_other: I feel that a lot of our policies and decisions are fear based. People that are making decisions are not actually doing the work and seeing the time it takes to do properly - staffing ratios are not being adjusted. Variations in rules between hospitals is also quite frustrating - staff being confused when they work multiple places. And patients being confused based on what they've heard from friends/family. We have nursing management issues at baseline on our floor, and this pandemic has only increased the poor communication & lack of leadership. I feel that going forward there will be permanent changes in how we provide medical care - some for the better. I am motivated to move forward with change following this crisis.

OE_upsetting:
Overwhelmed in ICU
Out of house x 7 weeks
Too busy in ICU Too light in office.
OE_positive:
Having a place to go.
NOT getting sick despite intense exposure

OE_upsetting: I missed my father's 70th birthday because I could not travel due to the department asking that physicians not leave the state.
OE_positive: There seems to be an attitude of sharing work better in my section compared to previously, which is nice because previously a lot of things would default to me.

OE_upsetting: The increase in stress and anxiety and not felling safe to go to work.
OE_positive: nothing
OE_other: nothing

OE_upsetting: My brother had to quarantine himself from his family due to his work in a jail in CT.  Also not being able to see family/friends
OE_positive: I became pregnant and it was quite surprising. however I think it is giving everyone (including myself) something happy to look forward to
OE_other: I mostly work in the university, however I do walk through the hospital daily (when I am working) and I find it disconcerting that workers sit together at the small round tables and chat/have lunch without their facemasks on (pulled down below their chin) and much closer than 6ft to each other.

OE_upsetting: I didn't experience any upsetting things.
OE_positive: The most positive thing I experience during the COVID-19 was how we all came together and worked as a team, even when I felt like I didn't belong due to being an outpatient worker. I felt appreciated by the supervisor and co-workers. Seeing patients faces full of gratefulness and thankfulness is what makes me hopeful and was the most rewarding to me. Loved when a patient said " why are you so good to me" and I responded because I care. This experience had make me feel strong and special as a Health worker.
OE_other: Working together in though times makes a difference.  Thank you all for your support!

OE_upsetting: The restrictions of social distances have left me feeling very isolated from my support system, and it has been harder to find ways to relax and unwind after workdays or on the weekends.
OE_positive: Having a supportive immediate team of colleagues to help each other stay positive.
OE_other: It did not seem that the hospital was appropriately responsive for employees that work in the hospital itself. I feel as though many more people/departments could have worked from home or at least had staggering schedules to allow some time at home and some at work which would have eased a lot of concerns about entering and sitting in the hospital all day among the COVID pandemic

OE_upsetting: Most upsetting was being sent to work on a COVID floor. It made me feel disposable because I was the only one. It has become a rewarding experience in the end. I understand the decision was best for the hospital and our patients but it took a personal emotional toll on me.
OE_positive: I feel grateful to be able to provide support to the staff on the COVID floor to which I was assigned. I was talking to one of the newer nurses who told me she was going home every morning (we worked night shift) crying and was anxious all the time. She said that this feeling was going away and was concerned that she was losing her compassion. We spoke for a while about how how it’s normal to adjust to stressful situations in order to continue doing her job each night. She told me later that our conversation was very helpful which made me realize that I had an actual contribution to the team. I’m really did feel supported and appreciated on the COVID unit.
OE_other: The hardest part is losing personal connections. I lost my staff when I was reassigned, I don’t even know what anyone looks like, I feel so robotic providing patient care behind the PPE, it’s so important to maintain human connections with kind words because we’ve lost the ability to use touch. I hope the newer nurses don’t leave the profession as a result of their COVID experiences, so many wonderful nurses, it would be such a loss.

OE_upsetting: I've had several patients die from COVID-19 without family or friends present at their bedside. I pronounced several of them dead on the same day. Although I have support from friends and family, it is difficult to understand the impact that can have without living through it.
OE_positive: I've had more time to talk to friends and family and I feel that some of these relationships have become closer as a result. I've had more time outside of work to spend outside.

OE_upsetting: Lack of PPE for clinic and when seeing patients, and guilt of using PPE when other workers do not have any.
OE_positive: Seeing some colleagues rise to the occasion and take leadership roles while providing good care for their patients
Seeing more appreciation for my work
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Patient death
OE_positive: Team has formed cohesiveness
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: I am incredulous that matters of life and death are in the hands of President Trump. He has shown a continual rejection of science, and works counter to the efforts of public health experts. He trumpets his successes even as the death toll mounts.
OE_positive: I am always grateful for the companionship of my wife, also an ER physician, and my 20-year-old daughter, forced home from college. I feel that although the disruption we're experiencing is unprecedented, we find that we do not worry about my daughter, who has type 1 diabetes, because she is safe in our home, in the short term, anyway. And although I am very disappointed that the School of Medicine was very quick to announce a salary freeze for its faculty--protecting its bottom line before its front line--I am grateful that I have a job and that I can contribute to society.
OE_other:
Disappointment that PPE was not uniform and more state-of-the-art. If this were NASA, I can't imagine that we would be asked to jury-rig a space helmet. 

Also, I think that all HCWs should have been tested for SARS-CoV-2 regularly.

OE_upsetting: Nothing big.  Just being isolated and being worried about my family's safety constantly.
OE_positive: Feel more connected emotionally to my family and friends and appreciate them more.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: My best friend's father died of COVID on Long Island.  I am devastated for my friend and his family.
OE_positive: Having an incredibly supportive family, friends, and spouse.
OE_other: No other than all of the people that I have worked with have been incredible.

OE_upsetting: People I know making statements thinking the pandemic is "made up." and not listening to guidelines.
OE_positive: increase in teamwork among the nursing staff.

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting thing to see is people protesting about their perceived loss of freedom related to stay at home orders and being asked to wear masks.  And the associated conspiracy theories against medical professionals.
OE_positive: The outpouring of support from some in the community.

OE_upsetting: Several fellow nurses in the ambulatory care setting I work in were unwilling to be re-assigned to in-patient to assist in patient care on the hospital floors.  I feel frustrated that this behavior was tolerated by our management, angry these nurses can't see beyond selfishness, and hesitant to work with them again as they do not demonstrate good team work ethics.
OE_positive: I was re-assigned to an in-patient floor in a supportive role.  The manager/nurses/techs/unit staff have been very appreciative of my assistance - I have made a positive difference in their day which gives me great satisfaction.  I have also seen many health care workers in various roles I have not seen in many years.  I am grateful to still be apart of this team-work culture.
OE_other: In hindsight, precautions could have been established sooner, as well as planning for the most efficient way to utilize ambulatory staffing.

OE_upsetting: My parents feel like I have abandoned them because I cannot visit them.
OE_positive: Improved communication between specialties

OE_upsetting: Unprotected exposure from a co-worker who was displaying obvious respiratory symptoms with potential exposure to my family as well.
OE_positive: Survival of active infection.

OE_upsetting: Nothing terribly upsetting.  Just mixed messages as we sort out the right thing to do
OE_positive: Good quality time with my family

OE_upsetting: not knowing if/when I will be reassigned to a COVID only unit for an undetermined amount of time and having to move away from my wife and children. Also concerned about the well being of my parents (mom w/advanced COPD, father w/a h/o two cancers).
OE_positive: all my loved ones have remain healthy-to date
OE_other: I'm tired of the constant masking and meticulous hygiene routine, and I wonder if I will ever be able to let my guard down at work again.

OE_upsetting: nothing
OE_positive: public is appreaciative of health care workers
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Being quarantined at home unable to go to church, visit relatives.
OE_positive: Not one death in our hospital, though we had some sick ICU patients. Made me feel like our hard work paid off
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Increased workload of sicker patients, and decreased PPE.
OE_positive: Public support has increased, its nice.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Working an understaffed floor for a week of nights. It was very stressful.
OE_positive: My partner from a long distance relationship is able to stay with me as his work situation changed due to social isolation.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: That the residency administration has not sought any resident feedback about proposed schedule changes and were slow to respond to initial PPE concerns. Resident concerns have continued to be dismissed by non-front line residency administrators, which is very frustrating.
OE_positive: Have continued to work with my psychiatrist about how to best control my anxiety and have am now less anxious than at any other point this year  (which is huge for me).
OE_other: Surprised that my work hours have been reduced during COVID to reduce resident burnout. The reduced work week (7 on/7 off) has been great!

OE_upsetting: Feeling like I don’t have a say in any thing. Getting “volun-told” to do things that were basically and expectation. Being worried that I would be fired if I spoke out about lack of PPE. Not getting hazard pay.
OE_positive: Being in touch with family and FaceTiming more bc everyone is home. The appreciation community has for HCWs

OE_upsetting: Nothing particularly upsetting comes to mind. My daughter not being able to play with her friends?
OE_positive: People getting better and going home after a month intubated!

OE_upsetting: We were moved to screen patients coming in to she Shoreline medical center.  I think the most upsetting thing was I felt unprepared and not trained (as it was on the job training) There is a lot of grey area with decision making as things are rapidly changing.  During one time a patient lied about being COVID + and if I hadn't asked a few more questions prior to letting the pt go in for her apt she would have been in the entire building.  For precaution after that I spent 7 days away from my son and family.  But it was at that time I realized how much weight had been placed on our shoulders.
OE_positive: I think overall being able to lessen others stress and anxiety has been a great experience.  It is not one specific situation, but many that I feel that by calmly and kindly talking to patients about process we are doing at Yale to protect them and also seeing others I work with do the same is great.  Our Old Saybrook team is one of a kind and I feel very lucky to work with such a dynamic group.
OE_other: Overall I think the hospital is doing a great job.  This is not pleasant for anyone, but I feel supported in my role.  I also believe my religion and practice of positive thoughts have helped me get through the initial high stress period into continuing to find a 'new' normal.

OE_upsetting: The failure of national leadership has left me fearful and enraged as I watch our country fall apart, particularly because of my children and the impact this will have on their lives.
OE_positive: Watching my colleagues step into roles they normally do not play to serve has inspired me tremendously.

OE_upsetting: Watching people suffer without control
OE_positive: my manager has been very supportive

OE_upsetting: No specific event, just watching my children miss out on things and the inability to plan for future events
OE_positive: The community support has been overwhelming
OE_other: I'm proud to work at my hospital and I feel fully supported by leadership and executive staff

OE_upsetting: One of colleagues from a former work place became sick with covid. He was intubated and in the ICU for weeks before recovering. He is in his early 30s. His wife is a physician, and we trained together in residency. My husband is also a physician. He has no chronic medical problems. It was difficult to see someone in a very similar position to my personal and family situation become so ill and maybe even close to death. I had prepared myself to see those with commodities and the elderly to suffer in this way. It hit too close to home.
OE_positive: I rarely spend time with my husband as we are both busy with differing schedules. We have never spent so much time together. We are both at home during similar hours since the onset of the crisis. We eat every meal together. We started playing tennis together again. We have not seen in our friends in more than a month. We are truly enjoying each other's company and embarked on a few projects together.
OE_other: The strangest part is that I am afraid to lose my job. Even though, I am needed more than ever in some ways to work. I see the financial hardship setting in. They wiped our previous schedule. I feel relieved every week when I get another week's schedule.

OE_upsetting: My kids asking if I was going to get sick and die
OE_positive: Being less "busy",  having more time to do things with my kids when not working at the hospital.

OE_upsetting: My wife is a healthcare worker in the outpatient setting and has been furloughed as they are not seeing routine patients
OE_positive: Support from everyone.  Feels great!
OE_other: Again, the support all around has been great.

OE_upsetting: Having to hand out an N95 to employees and tell them to reuse it and see the pain and fear in their eyes, not knowing if the mask will actually function as needed.
OE_positive: The fact that I have tested positive but did not experience severe symptoms and recovered.
OE_other: Not at this time.

OE_upsetting: Not upsetting but frustrating - management approach to practice operations is inconsistent and lacks clarity. frustrating to have to implement changes when they are all over the place
OE_positive: nothing
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: My fiancée's son is an alcoholic and recently he has gone off the wagon and is terribly out of control. We are presently looking for an inpatient program for him. Fingers crossed!! It just heightens the fear of what may happen to him and also will he expose himself, family or others to covid-19 due to this. It also feels like there really isn't much help out there for him as all resources are focused on Covid-19.
OE_positive: I have been with my fiancée for 14 years and have spent a lot more time with him due to him and I being home together more at different times throughout this. Happily I feel like it has brought us even closer. Also I feel like our co-workers have all been supportive of one another and continue to be a great group of people to work with.
OE_other: I don't particularly like that our administrators tell us that it is our duty to work and care for positive Covid-19 patients. When we are asked to care for these patients without the proper PPE and other cleaning practices in place, that puts us at a higher risk. We should not be sacrificing our health in order to care for the patient population.

OE_upsetting: I'm pregnant, so having people say things like "Oh my God I can't believe you're still working in the ER" has been difficult to manage. The fact that people question whether or not I am concerned for or taking proper precautions to protect my fetus is upsetting, but I know I am doing what I need to stay safe while continuing to work. I also have a team who tries to keep my contact with COVID patients as minimal as possible.
OE_positive: At my appointments with my OB, she thanks me for continuing to work and assures me I am not doing anything that puts me or my baby in jeopardy. There have been a lot of people who thank me, but her gratitude and reassurance feel different.

OE_upsetting: The most personally upsetting thing that has happened directly to me is the disruption in my children's childcare and school arrangements and watching them struggle to cope with new routines has been challenging; however, I am grateful for the robust state government response to this crisis and feel lucky that this is the worst thing that has happened to my family so far. However, I have been in contact with colleagues across the nation (I worked in NYC for 10 years prior to this job, which I started last year) and I have heard many upsetting things from close friends about their exposures and experiences with Covid-19, which has contributed to my own anxiety about how we as a society will be able to handle this situation.
OE_positive: I have been very grateful that my organization has made efforts (that were well communicated, which I appreciated) to acquire adequate PPE and train/fit us very quickly in the use of new brands of N95s, PAPRs, etc. Being prepared to safely do my job has been the most reassuring aspect of this, and gives me hope that I will be able to continue working in a way that does not excessively compromise my safety and that of my family.
OE_other:
I am appalled the the disorganized and inadequate response from our federal government to this global crisis. On May 8, 2020, I still can't order a test for Covid-19 on a community-dwelling, non-hospitalized patient at my institution because we haven't been able to source adequate numbers of nasopharyngeal swabs and we refuse to use sub-par oropharyngeal testing, a decision with which I am in agreeement. 

The fact that the federal government has not utilized every resource in its power to quickly and efficiently ramp up testing and contact tracing efforts is an unmitigated travesty and will result in far worse economic effects in our society, while we have to continue to rely on social distancing to manage this infection instead of proactive containment efforts. The fact that we are forced to approach this pandemic in the same exact way as the 1918 influenza pandemic, using public health approaches that are a century old, would be laughable if it weren't so tragic. We need more tests and a robust public health infrastructure to adequately address this crisis, and all the effective local leadership in the world is not going to be able to substitute for that. 

If you want to know how to support health care workers in this crisis, get us tests, contact tracing and PPE.

OE_upsetting: My finance and brother losing their jobs. My fiance losing his job and yet I am still burdened with rent and student loans.
OE_positive: Fiance and I have been exercising together more than before. It feels good to spend that time together.
OE_other: N/A

OE_upsetting: early on being told not to wear a mask while seeing patients
OE_positive: our teams really coming together and working on how to modify our operations in outpatient and hospital. good to be part of dynamic positive teams
OE_other: most medical associated workers feel proud to be able to do something

OE_upsetting: Patient with covid 19 dying unexpectedly after having improved substantially. Made me second guess my treatment plans
OE_positive: Bought a new home

OE_upsetting:
Loss of childcare leading to poor productivity.
Spouse losing job. Reduction in income/financial stress.
Not being able to see friends and family due to social distancing, made me feel sad and depressed
OE_positive: Sharing experience with people, bonding and connecting although not physically together

OE_upsetting: I live in a place where there is essentially no coronavirus, so I have thankfully not been confronted with disease/death. I have been most affected by my family's inability to come visit, which has meant that they have not been able to spend time with my infant son. This has been hard for both me and my parents. The added stress of being home more often has also put strain on my marriage.
OE_positive: It has been encouraging to see how quickly air pollution improved with travel restrictions in place

OE_upsetting: that this could go on for more than a year
OE_positive: connecting with friends and family via zoom
OE_other: My main worry as a high-risk person is that this will go on and that I shouldn't see patients in person which would be so sad for me.  Also I love to travel and have no idea when that will be possible.

OE_upsetting: Husband having to work and be gone from me and my 3 month old for 3 weeks at a time
OE_positive: Telemedicine and being able to spend more time with my baby

OE_upsetting: At the beginning of the pandemic, before I started working from home secondary to my pregnancy, I was wearing a mask proactively and other health care providers on my team questioned me for this decision. This was very frustrating.
OE_positive: The pandemic has made me realize how team oriented and caring people can be, going out of their way and risking their safety for the health of others.

OE_upsetting: A pediatric patient of mine coded but was able to be revived.
OE_positive: Together in isolation

OE_upsetting: Feeling like we have no control, the lack of not "knowing" information in regards to staffing, deployments, COVID patients, how to care for them, whom to refuse care to in the outpatient setting, when is it ok to bring patients in.. it is very unnerving not knowing/ having answers
OE_positive: more time with my children when I am home
OE_other: the staff directly involved in caring for these patient deserve more in compensation, the staff deployed deserve more recognition

OE_upsetting: family acutely ill and family dying in Italy. sad and hopeless there is nothing i can do. nervous, and anxious and worried about their health.
OE_positive: nature is healing

OE_upsetting: Lack of control or choices. Bored
OE_positive: People in society are helping each other.   Nicer to each other.  For the most part.  Makes me feel part of larger world.  Makes me smile.  All accept republicans and democrats.  They still can’t work together despite seeing society work together.  Spoiled over privileged self centered group of people.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Honestly things have been fine for me. My family and friends are healthy, I have a job (that I am working less at but still getting paid), I'm exercising more and eating healthier. I'm mildly anxious about the workload that will befall my predominantly elective surgery department when this all blows over.
OE_positive: People have honestly been really sweet to healthcare workers in all of this. From signs to billboards to free stuff from various companies I do actually feel that the reasonable people in society have our backs in all this. It is reassuring, despite the news wanting to make you think that the world is ending.
OE_other: I think YNHH has done a great job administratively in all of this to keep us safe.

OE_upsetting: Nothing specific my partner is immunosuppressed and undergoing chemo therapy and the increased risk is stressful.
OE_positive: The way my everyone has worked together.  One of my direct reports who got me a compliant laptop so I could work from home.
OE_other: I feel great sympathy for the trainees and medical students whose education is being so drastically impacted especially our incoming academic class.

OE_upsetting: i watched a co-worker get yelled at for asking a supervisor the proper protocol assisting a patient that previously tested positive for covid-19.
being healthcare worker is great but the other people especially my daughter’s teachers and friends’ parents are afraid of me, they think I will contaminate them
isolation at home. kids not in school. friends losing jobs. sheltering in place significantly more difficult than my job at the hospital
OE_positive: my kids being understanding of no birthday parties. sweet and accepting
OE_other: vvery few covid+ patients in san francsico. the anticipation of a surge at the beginning caused much more stress than work itself. media coverage is stressful. actual burden at work is low

OE_upsetting: Nothing
OE_positive: N/A

OE_upsetting: The fear of exposing my partner,who I live with in a small 1 bedroom apt, is a daily dread that hangs over me like a dangling sword above my head.
OE_positive: Patients and friends thanking me for what I do
OE_other: One concern is as a resident is that stress and hours increase during a pandemic, however, there are discussions of paycuts or benefit cuts. I am not sure how health care providers are protected during a health crisis.

OE_upsetting: Having COVID patients die after having cared for them for many weeks. I feel helpless.
OE_positive: Our team in the ICU has felt much more cohesive.

OE_upsetting: None

The initial change in hospital policy telling us that we no longer "required" nor allowed to wear N-95 to take care of COVID+ patients that were not intubated or on HFNC. I felt mistrust towards the hospital leadership. I felt they were not looking out for the front line providers. Part of knew that it was most likely due to limited and poor PPE supply, however, I had wished that they were transparent about that fact.
OE_positive: It's been nice working in my own department's wellbeing task force and helping others cope and get through the stressors of this pandemic. It's been great when people reach out to tell us that we've made a difference in helping them be more well.
