OE_upsetting: My work visa will expire soon. My application for permanent residency has been delayed. I am worried that I won't be able to get the request for work authorization approved on time. The worry of having to leave my job and leave the country and travel in the middle of the pandemic makes me anxious and sad.
OE_positive: I had a chance to connect with other colleagues and share experiences to relieve anxiety.
OE_other: Being able to provide care to the patients during the most challenging times in our lives gives me sense of meaningful purpose and makes me feel proud of myself that I am a doctor.

OE_upsetting: social isolation, limited access to community, vacations had to be postponed.
OE_positive: More support from others, more contact to people I have lost touch with in the past, through different apps, more tech savvy with zoom videos.
OE_other: Close community of staff and support, care for each other.

OE_positive: I have spent more time at home with my 27month old and 6 month old.

OE_upsetting: Difficulty in transferring a patient from an affiliated hospital to our quaternary center for NIPPV use in Covid-associated respiratory failure and comorbidities. It was worked out and the patient was cared for, but there was mild conflict that we resolved together that was initially frustrating.
OE_positive: Improved camaraderie in my division and in the hospital with good leadership, frequent discussion, and nimble adjustments to what is needed. it makes me proud of our department and division.

OE_upsetting: being forced by a doctor to "see" a covid+ patient despite knowing from the chart review that it was not necessary and explaining this to him multiple times.
OE_positive: productivity standards have been eliminated so I can actually spend the time with each patient that they need and deserve
OE_other: nope

OE_upsetting: My mother in law passed away and we were not able to have a funeral. I feel like there is no sense of closure. She did not pass away due to COVID19. She developed sepsis while inpatient. She was able to be sent home to pass away at home with family because no one could visit her in the hospital due to the pandemic. I feel very sad about the whole situation and feel like we were not able to grieve properly.
OE_positive: I was able to work from home for some of my shifts which made me feel more comfortable. My husband is a new police officer and was able to have 2 weeks off and then work 2 week and then 2 weeks off again. It was helpful because I didn't have to worry about my parents watching my daughter during that time and possibly becoming infected with the virus.

OE_upsetting: A patient that I saw without proper PPE tested positive for COVID 19 several days later. Nothing was done to ensure that I did not have COVID 19 and I was expected to continue working. It made me anxious and upset because I work with many cancer patients and patients in the ICU. Additionally my roommate has very bad asthma and I worry about infecting them.
OE_positive: We have been able to re-work our schedules to work more effectively for our patients and improve our overall satisfaction.
OE_other: I wish that our national government had taken a stronger approach toward things. Most hospitals are approaching things very differently and the inconsistencies do not bode well for research/learning from/about COVID 19. Also the inconsistencies in government decisions has created some animosities toward health care workers, which is stressful.

OE_upsetting: When covid first happened, I had to work much longer hours and it was very tiring.
OE_positive: The community put up thank you signs.
OE_other: Rush University Medical Center has done a terrific job keeping all employees informed, training us on how to properly wear PPE, and giving us the appropriate PPE.

OE_upsetting: Not being able to see extended family.
OE_positive: Husband delivering free lunches.
OE_other: no

OE_positive:
Coworkers on the same pay-grade pulling together when management is detached. 

When I was having a personally bad mental health day, my coworkers sincerely questioned if I was okay and banded together to ease the pressure of the job. No one in upper-management or the physicians do anything like that with the team. Just the lower employees banding together almost as war comrades.

OE_upsetting: Patient that was made DNR, almost coded and died because it took so long for team to come in proper PPE, and we wouldn't have been able to resuscitate her (and she was young) - felt extremely helpless
OE_positive: My program director leadership has been outstanding and so supportive

OE_upsetting: The residents at the senior care home are declining, mentally, emotionally and physically and the caregivers appear to be so burnt out, that the level of quality and care has declined as well. Also, our wedding was cancelled. It has been difficult to not see family and friends and to feel trapped without the freedom to typically come and go. Family members and loved ones are clearly stressed, consuming too much media, etc and it is upsetting to see people so frustrated and at a loss. There are feelings of hopelessness, depression, anxiety, frustration, isolation and loss of worker and personal rights.
OE_positive: Being more connected through virtual chats and phone calls. It made me feel connected.
OE_other: Initially, safety measures were not being taken as quickly as I would have liked to see for working in the health field and there were PPE shortages. Parking refuses to suspend my lease due to COVID19 and is forcing me to pay $40/month for a service I don't use as my location is solely in the senior community now. Our department forced us to purchase and pay for scrubs and recommended no jewelry, including my engagement ring. While I understand the precautions, it is frustrating to feel so much taken from you or asked of you financially when other companies are trying to help during this time, financially, I think there was no leniency in the purchasing of scrubs or the parking for example. This leads to feeling unappreciated and taken advantage of.

OE_upsetting: At the start of it all I felt as though we weren't making decisions quick enough and that we weren't taking folks concerns seriously.  Those first two to three weeks as schools shut down were probably the most stressful in my entire career.
OE_positive: I am finding myself experiencing more gratitude and truly enjoying my family and the decreased hustle and bustle.

OE_upsetting: Family members losing their jobs. This makes me angry.
OE_positive: Can't think of anything positive
OE_other: I am much less productive working from home. It is very stressful when connectivity to the VPN is poor

OE_upsetting: watching teammates get really rattled when caring for Covid patients.  It is difficult to be a bystander and only be the supportive listener.  I would prefer to help in a direct hands-on way... and I was not in a position to do that in my current role as RN Clinical Lead in the OR.  I am responsible for assigning staff to take care of covid patients, and then I have to help them deal with their anxiety and worries.
OE_positive: I am grateful that our hospital has been supportive of staff.  They have made sure we got our hours, they have found ways to deploy us to support roles (OR staff that helped with screening and testing) and they even gave us a bonus for working during the pandemic.
OE_other: Just that as an OR nurse, we have had to help with covid positive patients that had broken bones and needed surgery.  We had extensive training and PPE to help keep the team safe in the OR. and we have not had to do any floor nursing that would have been way out of our skill sets.  So we are happy to be working at BJI.  They have done a really great job keeping us employed and engaged in support roles for HHC.

OE_upsetting: At the beginning of the Pandemic out outpatient treatment program had no plans in pplace to protect patients or staff.  It took them 2 weeks to implement some changes and longer to implement adequate changes.  This was very frustrating as I was making suggestions which weren't being implemented.  It took 2 of us to implement the policy of taking patient's temperatures after more than a week of that being done at the main hosptital.  It was frustrating and scary.  At that point I definately felt like my health and that of our patients was not important to the hospital administration.  I was angry.
OE_positive: I love seeing all the hearts and feeling the communities appreciation.  I feel the work I do is important and appreciated.
OE_other: I am quite scared about what the future will be like.

OE_upsetting: N/A
OE_positive: N/A
OE_other: N/A

OE_upsetting: UPMC forcing non-essential parts of the hospital to remain open and ramp up schedules too quickly has further convinced me that they are a greedy machine working under the guise of patient care.
OE_positive: I was given the opportunity to work from home for some time, which has been a relief.
OE_other: no.

OE_upsetting: people close to me thought about getting weapons (like knives and guns) to protect themselves during what they thought would be civil unrest. The civil unrest never came, but now I know these things about people I love and care about, and that is really upsetting to me.
OE_positive: more time with my child at home

OE_upsetting:
We lost a 22 yo patient who has a 2yo son and had minimal comorbidities.  Watching her parents was heartbreaking, we do not allow visitors unless the patient is actively dying or already deceased.  We are too busy with patient care to give family members the attention they require for support. In the beginning, they only saw their loved one dropped at the hospital and then dead or dying.  We are trying to do video visits but again it must be terrifying for them to see their loved one proned and intubated. I like to do the video calls it helps to reconnect and give purpose to my work. 
It is terrible that they cannot visit.  I can see the staff getting frustrated with families for calling so frequently.  
This disease seems to kill people randomly, to many young healthy people are dying.  I find that I am irrationally angry with coworkers whose units/ work have not been affected by Covid, when they are posting videos of themselves and their staff laughing and joking at work and when they voice petty complaints.  I find myself very happy to be alone at home watching cable TV shows with no news or commercials.
OE_positive: One of our employees' 83 y.o. father in law transferred to us because an outside hospital gave him no chance to live.  He was vented, proned, on pressors and he recovered & was discharged home!  He is weak and will need PT but otherwise doing great!
OE_other:
I think we could deal with this better if there was an end in sight.  I could pace myself if I knew how long it would last, but not knowing makes me wonder if I can do my job well for the long haul.  I am a manager and try to be a role model for my staff, I do not want to get negative or burnt out because it my negativity would become infectious to my staff. 
Also I am not sure how the "new " normal will look, I am not sure we have enough resources for business as usual & Covid.

OE_upsetting: I have experienced a breakup with a partner. It made me feel even more isolated at this time.
OE_positive: Having my friends and family there for constant support. I didn't realize how important they are.

OE_upsetting:
With my very first COVID-19 person under investigation, we were preparing to intubate due to the patient's increased respiratory distress. Our floor hadn't had many COVID patients previous to this and policies were changing every day - it was overwhelming to try to keep up.

I was in my patient's room with a fellow RT and resident consulting the patient's deteriorating condition. We all had N95+ masks donned at this time, the patient was actively coughing and suctioning secretions. Meanwhile, my manager was outside the room yelling at those entering (the RT and resident now present in the room) that we shouldn't be wasting N95+ masks due to the shortage.

At this time, it was unknown whether the patient had COVID (test was pending) and we were concerned because the patient was actively coughing and suctioning secretions. Also, we were discussing intubating - which an aerosolizing procedure. At that moment, I felt unsafe and belittled for both myself and my coworkers by using the PPE we were thought to be using. I was angry and anxious for the upcoming intubation event that hadn't been performed on my unit with a COVID patient yet, all the while angry and unprotected by my management.

Since that event, I had severe anxiety about whether we were actually being adequately protected with necessary PPE or not. Whether our hospital was changing policies about PPE just to protect themselves or to actually protect the frontline workers.
OE_positive: Our unit was able to provide ICU care along with ECMO support for a young, pregnant patient who tested positive for COVID. She made it off ECMO and is now at home recovering (baby is okay too!).

OE_upsetting: The lack of following recommended guidelines by health care workers. Makes me feel like they are less intelligent than I had assumed.

OE_positive: Getting a little bit of rest -  I was able to work from home for a little bit and able to catch up on some much needed rest since I didn't have to get up 2hrs before my scheduled time to work.
OE_other: I'm proud of the team I work with!  Everyone is already great to work with, but even in tough times like these it has not changed anyone's attitude and personality.  The University of Iowa Community is blessed to have a team like this on the front lines.

OE_upsetting: I asked a question during a Zoom meeting about how leadership was going to protect laboratory workers when dealing with leaking COVID-19 specimens that are received in the pneumatic tube station when we are not allowed to wear N95 masks (the tube station will aerosolize the droplets leaking from the specimens). Leadership responded by saying that the virus is not airborne like TB (and completely denied the possibility of inhaling aerosolized droplets containing the virus) and that we should not be concerned by handling the leaky specimens because we would be unlikely to contract COVID-19. FOUR of my co-workers in the microbiology laboratory alone have tested positive for COVID-19 and they have all been handling the samples for testing. I feel angry and I know for a fact that nobody cares about the laboratory employees' safety when performing any testing, not just COVID-19 testing.
OE_positive: A gas station employee offered me free coffee on my way to work. I felt appreciated.
OE_other: This hospital does not pay their laboratory workers what they are worth. It took away retirement contributions, yearly raises, and furloughed us without pay. It has not supplied us with appropriate face masks while making wearing one a requirement. It has forced employees who are immunocompromised to come to work and handle specimens from PUIs and perform COVID-19 testing.

OE_other: Working in a hospital has given me a true perspective regarding the pandemic that has allowed me to educate friends and family members on how real the situation is.

OE_upsetting: when helping an elderly patients walk up a big step into a small space to be tested it is unavoidable for me to maintain distance and skin to skin contact when they grab my arm for help. I am only wearing a surgical mask and gloves, patient is wearing mask. We are told that the next patient can't go in to the space for 10 minutes due to ventilation system.  I am expected to clean the room during those 10 minutes.  I feel like I am protecting patients but my employer is not concerned about protecting me.  I should be able to wait 10 minutes to go into clean the room and have disposable protection.

OE_upsetting: Our office was closed.  The first day that it was closed a gentleman having chest pain, saw sign for Michigan Medicine and pulled into our parking lot seeking emergency care.  Because our doors were closed and locked, he didn't have anyone to offer help.  He collapsed on the sidewalk and was in cardiac arrest.  I wasn't aware until paramedics arrived and I helplessly watched them work on him.  He died.  It drove home the cost to all of society of the dramatic changes that had to occur to our health care system.  I still suspect strongly that he died of COVID, although I will never know.  The paramedic team that worked on him did not wear PPE (not even simple surgical masks) and I am haunted by the wonder if any of them became ill.

I performed a CT scan on a patient who lied about having no symptoms so I was not wearing the proper PPE (I just wore a surgical mask) and the findings in his scan were suspicious for Covid. He is currently awaiting Covid test results, having to wait for his results has made me anxious about my health.
OE_positive: Performing daily portable CXR on Covid patients and seeing their lungs starting to improve

OE_upsetting: My Father in law had a GI bleed and was in another hospital , it was very difficult to coordinate care.
OE_positive: it feels like staff have bonded more as we go through this together.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: An old friend died of a non-COVID-19-related illness.  The funeral and morning rituals were limited to only his immediate family for safety reasons.  This event highlighted the general fragility of our lives and the loneliness compounded by the pandemic.
OE_positive: Our divisional team has pulled together to enact good policies as a group.

OE_upsetting: Seeing fellow health care workers in the hospital not adhering to universal masking
OE_positive: More regular contact with family and close friends by videochat
OE_other: My previous detestation and profund loathing for the Giant Orange Narcissistic Fraud in the White House, and his cowardly coconspirators in the Republication Party, has grown astronomically.  His disregard for public safety is breathtaking and amounts to murder by disempowerment of public health and science.

OE_upsetting: I was in the park with my kids in a space that was far enough from other people that they could actually run around. They weren't wearing masks (because they were far away from anyone else) and some guy came up to me and told me they should really be wearing masks in a very directive tone. He had just passed another father with two kids without masks doing the exact same thing but said nothing to that dad. It was so frustrating because we've been working so hard to work with the kids at home who just need to get out and run around. They were >30-50 ft from other people. It was like the end of the rope - I was just so exhausted from trying to manage anything that I didn't need anyone judging how I was managing my children (who are 5 and 7 and refuse to wear masks without a major fight).  A similar episode happened 1 week earlier but we were >50 yards from anyone and someone yelled at the top of their lungs to judge us.
OE_positive: Spending time with my kids - I love being around them and being a part of their schooling, as hard as it is to try to work with them from home.  As a working mom, there's always this part of you that feels like you're not being a good mom because you're working too much (I also travel a lot for work).  I just love being able to have both parts of my life: my work that I'm really passionate about and my kids who I love more than life itself (even though it sometimes feels like neither is working well!)
OE_other:
I'm not working in the hospital - I'm working from home.
On the last panel about coping - my major coping mechanisms (in life generally and now) are exercise and friends.  I've been exercising 5-6 days/week (which I haven't done since medical school) and talking with friends more often than I do regularly - both have had a really positive impact.

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting thing is probably phone calls about/from my mother in assisted living.  Since I am fearful about exposing her, there is little I can do to help.  This makes me feel frustrated and powerless.
OE_positive: Generally the most positive thing is members of the health care team working together.  I am most hopeful that the tightness of the bond among members of the health care team will strengthen.  Even orthopedic doctors have seemed kind and supportive.  This makes me feel optimistic about the future of health care(in some ways).
OE_other: I have decided that the stages of dealing with a pandemic in health care are as follows: PAIICB.  1) Paralysis(because of fear), 2) Intellectualization(attempting to understand and learn about the virus), 3) Interest(renewed interest in helping patients) 4) Compassion(for those suffering the effects, and the scale of those effects), and 5) Burn out(as compassion capacity is overly burdened)

OE_upsetting: Hard to say
OE_positive: Spending time with family
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Having to stay on video chat with patients all day for outpatient visits while my exhausted wife (who is not getting her usually working part time in the hospital but has not been given shifts) loses her patience with the kids downstairs
OE_positive: working outside on weekend, mended fence and finally felt i had something to show for my work
OE_other: Have felt unsupported by health system as expectation is to work from home but i don't have the tools to make this feasible, ie my broadband frequently hangs up, my laptop is slow, the work computer i remote into is slow, and i need time saved on my schedule so i can periodically relieve my wife in the care of our 3 kids. The hospital system makes overtures to make this easier (ie offering online classes for kids and buying me a 2nd monitor) but remain primarily interested in keeping patient visits high to salvage billing (I continue to have very full schedules and no where to book patients). I was chastized for working from my academic office even though this would have been very low risk and exponentially more workable for my home circumstances.

OE_upsetting: Finding out my hospital was going to make up for lost revenue by cutting benefits and furloughing 1,400 FTE employees. The majority of these cuts are to those who were active in taking care of COVID patients. It is worse when I know that our health system has very deep pockets and that there were other ways other than having employees take the brunt of the cuts. This has left me extremely angry and frustrated!!
OE_positive: I was transferred from an outpatient oncology clinic to work inpatient medical wards caring solely for COVID patients. I felt very welcomed and appreciated by the other professionals I worked with. The comradery was very strong among all of us, including many of us who were transferred from other services. I made strong professional connections and friendships from my time on on the COVID units.
OE_other:
I worked in an inpatient, non-ICU unit, so luckily I did not have to experience the large amount of death that those units experienced. 
I will say that I am extremely frustrated, even angry, with those hospital administrators, the federal government, and those who deny or downplay the situation, believe it is a conspiracy theory, riot/revolt against public health policies, and treat healthcare workers with malice (stopping employees getting to work, calling employees "fake" or "actors", etc). These feelings can become overwhelmingly negative and can consume me at times. I know that many of my colleagues have the same feelings. These feelings can become strong enough that I question my wanting to work in the modern healthcare system.
I will also say that the front line healthcare workers, including but not limited to physicians, PA/NPs, nurses, PT/OT, RT, techs, and environmental services, have been incredible in adjusting, adapting, and thriving all in the mode of helping those who need our help the most at this time. The compassion, charity, and willingness to sacrifice for our patients is inspiring and reminds me of why I work in healthcare.

OE_upsetting: Learning about the deaths of people I know personally (friends, neighbors). So far none of my family or extended family members have been infected.
OE_positive: I have appreciated zoom calls with family and friends, and especially with my elderly parents. I see them regularly by video calls and we talk more than once a week, whereas in the past we would only talk by phone once weekly at most.
OE_other: It worries me when people say that this will all be "back to normal" soon. I don't think we will ever go completely back to the way things were before the pandemic. I believe this has forever changed how we will practice medicine. I do believe that we will be able to go back to an open society without social distancing or masks once there is sufficient herd immunity and a vaccine, but those things are a long way off.

OE_upsetting: Being pressured to perform endoscopy on a patient who was dying of COVID-19 and seeing a necrotic stomach. It made me feel frustrated and sad watching the nurse struggle to keep the patient alive. The patient’s sudden decline and trying to help the family cope with the stress was depressing.
OE_positive: Division coming together with meetings and supporting one another makes me happy and appreciative to be part of my section
OE_other: Teamwork and camaraderie are essential for success

OE_upsetting: dealing with coworkers who were feeling overwhelmed and manifesting it as irritation with me.  Makes me feel less good as a leader.
OE_positive: Watching our hospital staff come together in designing and staffing for COVID+ patients, with people willingly volunteering for extra tasks that were needed to be done.  Proud

OE_upsetting: I experienced a breakup prior to the pandemic - it is hard not to feel lonely during this time. I feel lonely/depressed.
OE_positive: My mom came to stay with me - it makes me feel safe.

OE_upsetting: The terrible response by the federal government to the pandemic and the realization we have as many deaths from COVID as China had cases. OE_positive: Helping my neighbors, patients, community and friends contend with the epidemic. I am glad I can use my knowledge to help others.

OE_upsetting: When I tested positive
OE_positive: An ex-boyfriend reached out to me via phone call and knowing that he cared made me feel loved

OE_upsetting: As an Assistant Nurse Manager on a COVID-ICU, I got very stressed when the hospital was figuring out what we could do about my immunocompromised and pregnant nurses. They had to work on our unit for a little longer than I was comfortable with before we were able to get them either reassigned to a non-COVID unit or allowed pregnancy leave 2 weeks before their babies were born. There are a lot of risks I am willing to take, and I trust the PPE that we have; but it's stressful when I have more people to consider than just myself. By God's grace, no staff members on our COVID ICU have gotten sick over the past few months; so this has helped. But that's where I wish I was just a staff nurse at times - so I can always take one for the team and just be a team player without feeling responsible for 90 other staff members.
OE_positive: See our team really rise to the challenging occasion has been incredible. We have such an amazing team here, and I wouldn't change it for the world. People are coming up with innovative ideas to provide the highest quality and the safest care possible, and I love seeing people get more involved than they are normally. Challenges truly do bring us even closer together, and it's true for a unit that was already close-knit.

OE_upsetting: I was on disability for a few months and came back in the middle of this pandemic. It was a little overwhelming learning new ways to handle my job duties to protect myself from exposure.
OE_positive: My coworkers supporting me and helping me learn the new ways things are being done.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Saw a child with severe multisystem inflammatory disease. Made me realize children are truly at risk, including my own.
OE_positive: Support from colleagues, family and friends.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: I have been lucky in that one event has not in particular impacted me personally.  The most upsetting thing is constantly trying to figure out how to find time for my work (which I want to be able to do), my husband's work, and childcare for my two year old and the child I am currently pregnant with.
OE_positive: The most positive thing is that both my husband and I have been able to maintain our jobs.
OE_other: The constant anxiety, especially because I see patients outpatient without knowing their status prior to going in the room, is exhausting. Also, the impact on women with children is beyond what anyone realizes unless they are the one doing it.

OE_upsetting: Sending my child back to daycare with uncertainties
OE_positive: Productivity with research with faculty having extra time; getting to work at home for 8 weeks with my son even though it was difficult
OE_other: I feel safer working in the hospital as a researcher than going to the store.

OE_upsetting: Generalized isolation, fear of contacting the virus. Fear of dying alone, without being able to see loved ones. No particular incident occurred
OE_positive: Community cohesiveness- banding together for donations, advertisements marketing appreciation for healthcare workers
OE_other:
Although I’ve always had a surgical mask, I only have an N95 for resuscitations or AGPs. My hospital is reusing and sanitizing these. If this is truly protective- why only start now? Current practices go against all previously “known” infection prevention strategies. I feel deceived, although I’m not sure if it’s by prior infection prevention teams and regulatory bodies, or by the current hospital administrators reiterating the safety of our daily practices at this time.
Im interested to see the future response/adherence to previous standard isolation policies surrounding disposable PPE- will people forever fear shortages and thus continue to reuse equipment even after the pandemic is over? Will they hoard PPE once it becomes widely available? Will they continue to respect regulatory ‘standards’ that are currently eliminated?
I’m disappointed that something of such magnitude was needed to encourage humanity as a whole to appreciate one another- to appreciate the contributions of all “essential” personnel, not just those in the medical field. I’m eager to see if/when these feelings and this generalized mood of gratitude will disappear.

OE_upsetting: Two of my child had covid and I felt sad knowing that it most likely came from me

OE_other: Scary

OE_upsetting: Losing my dear friend. He was not taken care of in the way he should have been at the hospital he was taken to by ambulance. testing for covid happened way too late and he had already passed away by then. It made me feel very angry/upset and sad
OE_positive: the respect and appreciation from the community, random people at the grocery store seeing me with my scrubs on and work badge came and thanked me for my service.

OE_upsetting: I just returned from maternity leave--it was very very nervewracking for me to see the images from NYC frontlines and think that I was going to return to work in a similar scene.  I pictured my newborn having to grow up not remembering who I was or how we spent our 16 weeks together and felt very guilty and sad. I started recording videos of us during my last days of maternity leave talking to her and telling her what has happened in the world and why I might not be there for her in the future.
OE_positive: Colleagues have been very supportive, friends have been supportive sending masks and PPE.  I felt like my non healthcare worker support is more indicative of people taking the pandemic seriously and not just brushing the crisis aside or deeming it falsified.
OE_other: Our volumes have been manageable for now.  There was more of a PPE supply and protocol upon my return in mid April, so I felt a little more prepared and confident in working clinically.

He has had to hear all heartbeats and visual ultrasounds via facetime without being able to hold my hand or share contact during these joyous events during my pregnancy. It has made me feel like a single mother and that I am robbing him of all experiences watching his first child grow in utero.
OE_positive: My husband has been able to work from home full time and I get to see him more often on my days off during the daytime. It makes me feel happy because I am catching up on time spent with him we'd normally lose with him being at his office.
OE_other: I wish the United States was not reactive but proactive with the pandemic. I feel as though the health and wellness of hospital staff members was not top priority and that we were essentially sacrificed for politicians to "learn as we go" as a country.

OE_upsetting: Patient family members aren’t allowed to visit COVID positive patients even if they are dying or have deceased. Patients die alone and it is traumatic to watch.
OE_positive: People showing their support to our unit. The public has been donating food and sending words of encouragement to us nurses.
OE_other: We need a president that supports us frontline workers. Trump does not. He doesn’t get it.

OE_upsetting: Just the frequent (usually daily but sometimes hourly) PPE recommendation changes and nurse's week announcement across the nation about nurses not getting raises, pay cuts, and job loss . It makes me feel like our administrators do not appreciate that nurses are on the frontline, risking their lives. Some of the nation is seeing us as hero's while our administrators are proving they see us as expendable and replaceable.
OE_positive: Communities rallying to get PPE to hospitals.

OE_upsetting: I have felt upset by the demands of my co-workers toward hospital leadership, indicating that we are entitled to more pay and protection. While I agree that having better PPE is essential, I believe that our hospital has done the best that it can in the circumstances and that we signed up for this and do not require better pay. This level of frustration seeds discontentment and poor morale in the team when we need to focus more on building each other up and making the most of the circumstances.
OE_positive: Support from hospital leadership in the form of emails and personal reaching out.

OE_upsetting: Offered a raise then having that raise taken away. This made me feel like the work I was doing was not important and risking my own health was not worth it.
OE_positive: Appreciation from patients
OE_other: Seeing other people not practice social distancing on social media has affected my mental health and has made me feel like the work I am doing doesn't matter. The national government has also made me feel this way.

OE_upsetting: the only thing I can answer for this is that the most upsetting thing to me personally is the cancellation and uncertain resumption of schools. I have great anxiety about my children's education.
OE_positive: plans to move the family to a better living situation - not particularly COVID related - just upsizing as we grow.

OE_upsetting: My wife is pregnant and I had to refuse to come to work for the clinic to change its policies on social distancing and mask wearing.
OE_positive: Finding out our baby-to-be's gender! It's a boy!
OE_other: The federal government's response to the crisis has made me stop supporting the Democratic Party. I never supported the Republicans, and was already close to dropping the Democrats, but their support of another bailout of corporate America let me to lose the last remaining shreds of hope I had for the party.

OE_upsetting: getting exposed and my hospital not knowing what to do because they were not prepared.  I wanted to get tested and it took a week to get an answer.
OE_positive: I got to spend more time with my family in my household.
OE_other: It was frustrating to be on the front lines and not have a good plan in place to handle the pandemic. administration making decisions on PPE that aren't facing it everyday.  The government was not very prepared or take the pandemic seriously enough and reacted to late.

OE_upsetting: Cancelled travel plans - disappointed but understandable
OE_positive: More time to spend on personal life/activities/exercise

OE_upsetting: Wrong media ad/news
OE_positive: -Being able to provide care of patients in this difficult time

OE_upsetting: Possibly having to postpone my wedding date, missing niece and nephew birthday parties and family events. Makes me feel worried and sad as that is what has brought me joy in my normal life.
OE_positive: Being surrounded by helpful coworkers who are willing to discuss feelings/the world/ our predicament. It is nice to be able to discuss with people who understand the situation at the hospital/home life. Especially because my significant other doesn't work at the hospital.
OE_other: The most difficult part is not being able to separate yourself from it. You hear about COVID at work, then go home & family discusses with how you're feeling/TV/social media, etcs. I wish I could leave it at work, although it is hard to because it's all over the place, feel like I can't get away from it.

OE_upsetting: Developing quarantine plans to keep family members from visiting their dying loved ones with the chaplain service
OE_positive: Developing process to quickly and effectively test hospital employees with outdoor, drive up clinics

OE_upsetting: My husband and child being sick early on in the pandemic and not having the ability to get them tested and not knowing if they would be ok
OE_positive: Spending more time with my family
OE_other: Rewarding to be with patients when they are otherwise alone. But so scary to be putting my life at risk when I have young kids at home. And just sad to not know when I'll be able to see my family again. But this too shall pass. Hopefully at least!

OE_upsetting: Not being able to see extended family/members and managing stress of homeschooling.
OE_positive: Spending more time with my daughter, more time at home (less of a commute)
OE_other: People have know idea how hard it is to fulfill work expectations and homeschool while you are a health care professional working from home.

OE_upsetting: Prior to COVID, I was working 8 hour days, with an occasional 9-10 hour day. I am now working 12 hour days with minimal breaks and have heard nothing from my supervisor about my sudden increase in hours. Additionally, our hospital went weeks without requiring payment for parking, which greatly lessened the burden of having to come into work during this time. They have since reimplemented payments for parking, meaning I will now have to start taking the bus again. I find this increased risk for exposure concerning, and again, have heard nothing from my supervisors. The most upsetting part about working during this time has been feeling as though you are going above and beyond and yet no one seems to care that your work takes a serious toll on you.
OE_positive: Being lucky enough to not have to worry about work or housing issues.
OE_other: I think there are a lot of behind the scenes people who are being overworked and looked over. We like to focus on our nurses and doctors - and we are especially thankful for their sacrifices and hard work. We need to acknowledge that their experiences will not be the same as other hospital staff and shouldn't be the only stories we look to use. Thank you for doing this survey and allowing for other narratives to be shared.

OE_upsetting: Most upsetting personally is not being able to go see friends or family on my days off. I cancelled a vacation and decided it would be better for me emotionally to work instead of sitting home alone in my apartment for 7 days. I feel sad that my parents have to isolate by themselves without any family nearby.
OE_positive: I felt a sense of purpose at work. I knew I was working to help the system whereas usually, I feel jaded about my healthcare system.

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting has been the protesting and selfishness of individuals rioting and then thanking us it’s a slap in the face.  The fact that things are opening back up and people lack courtesy to stay 6 feet or wear a mask.  Because I work in a pediatric hospital and parents are permitted the intermittent attitude from parents when they need to stay in rooms of children have covid pending. Some situations have shortened my patience
OE_positive:
I have saved money 
Gotten closer to my co workers 
Have a better respect for life
OE_other: I would like to thank the people that donated to our hospital who are grateful and can follow direction !

OE_upsetting: It isn't one thing specific. I am upset with the response and hearing everyone's opinion. The lack of accountability from the federal government, the lying from all leaders, the CDC changing language just to protect themselves. It feels like we're all being lied to. And due to that, everyone is trying to figure it out for themselves which is causing an explosion on social media, heightened emotions, anger, fear. It's just frustrating and greatly impacting morale at work. The little men look to the leaders for answers and a direction, and they're a fucking mess and it leaves us just to figure it out. Pardon my language. But you get it.
OE_positive: I guess exercise in general. I went on a long 10 mile walk alone and did some exploring. It just let me feel free. I ordered a stationary bike for when it's raining outside or when I want to avoid people haha. I also had a nice talk with a delivery man for 20 minutes and he sang me a song. We're all just looking for a connection at this point.
OE_other: I'm tired of the lying and the false information. It's difficult enough for me, with a medical background, to know the truth. Do I believe my health care institution? Do I believe the CDC who changed their policies? Do I believe our government? (YEAH RIGHT) or do we believe Joe Shmoe on facebook? because it seems like everyone else is believing that guy. Even if the facts don't align with our resources, we still deserve the truth. Even if we don't have N95s and maybe this virus has the potential to be airborne (even with the flush of a toilet) let's tell people that and militarize our supplies instead of making it so damn political. And enough with the graphs! People are not reading these graphs in a sensible way and it is just insanity. All in all, the lack of accountability and lies coming from above is frustrating and exhausting. I miss my family and my friends. Now my only social life involves work because I am in my late 20s and live alone. The social isolation and false information are the driving force of the negativity circulating this country.

OE_upsetting: I haven't hugged my mother since March. I still see her weekly, though
OE_positive: My interest in my job has been completely rejuvenated, I have never been more excited to be a doctor. It is a privilege to be in the role. This is a once in a lifetime challenge and I want to step up to that challenge.
OE_other: People need Islam

OE_upsetting: My whole family got sick early on in March, some fevers, and we had to quarantine and that was very scary. For weeks I would wake up and think about all of the people I had seen in the week or so before and how they would do with COVID. Now looking back I can remember how awful that felt, but attribute it more to how scared everyone was at the time, so that level and type of anxiety has definitely improved.
OE_positive: A few of my primary care patients have had it and seeing them get better and do well has helped put a more positive view of it, rather than focusing on the news and our hospitalized folks. But I think the biggest improvement has just been allowing everything to settle over time, knowing that our numbers are stable, that New York's numbers are coming down, it doesn't feel as apocalyptic.
OE_other: I think there is also some guilt that our hospital has done generally well through this. We were never overwhelmed, there was good, consistent messaging from the admin and infection control, we haven't run out of PPE (though we've shifted the types of things that we are using). Now it is hard to look out at all of the other places around the country and around the world where sharing some of the burden would be really beneficial, but we're here, doing fine. The inequities are overwhelming, as is the feeling that we were so pigeon-holed early on to where even other cities didn't matter as much.

OE_upsetting: rationing/stewarting limited treatments for sick patients.
OE_positive: I was able to volunteer in an important way that helped my community.  My skill set was useful in this regard.
OE_other: I have only experienced minor inconveniences  along the way, while my colleagues in other cities are truly struggling.  Its hard trying to balance protecting  your family and immediate social support system, while trying to live up to your oath.

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting thing is the inability to perform human gestures around tragedy and death, such as sitting near someone, looking at them clearly in the eyes without masks and face shields, reaching out and touching an arm, or giving a hug.  These gestures allow me to do my two jobs of critical care and palliative care with my humanity intact, and not being able to do them makes it infinitely more difficult to have hard conversations or provide support during the death of a child.  I do not feel like I am making the same type of authentic, human connection with the families of my patients because of social distancing and PPE.  This lack of human connection makes my job almost impossible and has exponentially increased my stress and distress.
OE_positive: My off-service time at home has been less hurried/busy, with all of my children's activities being canceled and our calendar essentially cleared.  This has also meant fewer distractions / other things to think about to distract me from my work at the hospital.
OE_other: As a pediatric intensivist, we have thankfully had many fewer cases than our adult colleagues, and our units have not been overwhelmed by COVID patients to any degree.  However, we had to implement countless practice changes, policy changes, visitation restrictions, etc as a result of COVID, none of which made our jobs any easier or more efficient (quite the opposite), all of which resulted in countless more meetings and emails, and all of which caused increased stress on our families of otherwise critically ill patients.  Furthermore, I personally have not felt like I can receive any of society's gratitude toward "health care workers on the front lines" as I have not been taking care of many COVID patients.  Therefore, we have not had the extra support / morale lift / camaraderie that seems to be apparent in other "COVID units" - at least as "advertised" by news media, social media, and commercials.  This has led me to feel unappreciated for the incredibly hard work I do every day with critically ill children outside of the COVID-19 pandemic, and makes me feel more isolated, like I'm not part of the "big health care team" who has come together on the "front lines."

OE_upsetting: Nothing has happened personally to me, it is the general sense of sadness and despair in society that has upset me
OE_positive: The stories of people giving to those in need

OE_upsetting: At first everyone was very supportive towards healthcare providers and me as a nurse. I felt appreciated and supported. Now things have shifted and over time I have noticed that people walk across the street when they see me in my scrubs and my friends don't want to see me because of my job. It has felt increasingly isolating throughout this whole pandemic.
OE_positive: It has been really cool to see how the ED team has come together at my hospital and supported one another throughout this difficult time.

OE_upsetting: My 102 year old mom died. Uncontrolled tears and sadness
OE_positive: calling friends more
OE_other: fear of unknown

OE_upsetting: working in the trauma bay while being in full PAPR with limited staff and families not able to be with their child. Made me feel sad lonely for the child/the parents
OE_positive: swabbing more negatives than positive
OE_other: I do not feel like a hero. I do not like being called a hero. While I did sign up to help others - I did not sign up to work without adequate PPE so it makes my job weird.

OE_upsetting:
1) lack of masks and social distancing on public transportation and on sidewalks (with more tents/encampments) and increase in unsafe behaviors and crime  --> makes me feel scared, angry that the city isn't providing enough resources to manage homelessness, risk of transmission, and crime

2) seeing our patients (primarily people with mental illness who are experiencing homelessness) be marginalized and excluded from containment strategies --> makes me feel helpless, frustrated, angry
OE_positive: potential for chronically homeless people to have a gateway to housing through shelter-in-place mandates

OE_upsetting: When I developed respiratory symptoms that were suspicious for COVID. At that time, I self quarantined, felt much more alone, and worried about potential bad outcomes.
OE_positive: Feeling appreciated for the work that I do by friends, neighbors, etc.
OE_other: Note that I disagree with your questions re: appropriate PPE. N-95 masks (rather than regular surgical masks) are not necessary for most interactions with COVID-positive patients, unless they are intubated or getting aerosol-generating procedures.

OE_upsetting: seeing patients die where I could not help, made me feel helpless and hopeless
OE_positive: unity amongst co-workers and hospital staff along with our community
OE_other: difficult and challenges everything I have worked so hard for

OE_upsetting: No single substantially upsetting event
OE_positive: Overall more patient and supportive environment with colleagues, leading to more connection and reassurance
OE_other: Very few pediatric patients, but the efforts to both minimize risk of infection and conserve PPE are moderately onerous and interfere substantially with work flow, creating considerable stress.

OE_upsetting: I tried to volunteer in New York City as a critical care provider but was unable to reach the volunteer contact to go help. Instead, I worked from home since my hours on the unit were reduced. I felt useless and helpless as someone who could potentially help my colleagues in NYC but unable to go help.
OE_positive: I was sent a homemade mask from a family friend showing her appreciation for my work.

OE_upsetting: Being told that due to respiratory symptoms (COVID negative), even though policy stated that I was not allowed to come in to work, the absence would be unapproved and if I continued to call off, it would be multiple unapproved absence occurrences, even with FMLA appoval. It is frustrating being caught between policies and having to go through multiple departments to get answers.
OE_positive: Grown closer to some coworkers who feel similarly about the changes that occurred in our department as result of all supervisors working from home for the entirety of the pandemic thus far.
OE_other: Since the hospital is on a hiring freeze, and our department has been short staffed since before the pandemic started, and all supervisors are working from home, the workload and lack of management is overwhelming.

OE_upsetting: I feel sad that I can not see my family, especially new nieces/nephew.
OE_positive: Being close with my coworkers and being able to debrief with them and talk about stressful situations has made me feel more hopeful.  It is nice having friends that are able to know exactly what you are going through.
OE_other: I feel the hardest part about being on the front lines is the ever changing nature of what we are doing for patients and how we are doing it.  Especially in the beginning, the most stressful part was having to read 10 e-mails every day to get the most updated recommendations on PPE for certain types of patients or procedures.

OE_upsetting: Supervisors/program directors belittle the pandemic and not advocating for resident safety amidst the pandemic. It makes me feel not heard and extremely frustrated about the poor leadership and little care for resident safety.
OE_positive: Exercising when the city celebrates healthcare workers at 8 pm. It's a beautiful time and an uplifting feeling.

OE_upsetting:
I have a friend that I am very close with. She is a year older than me (26), and we met as I was her clinical instructor at my previous job. After she graduated, she took a per-diem position within our radiology ultrasound department, and then when I left for my current role at HUP MFM, she filled into my prior position.

She is a first generation American, and lives with her mother, father, adult sister, and younger sister and brother. She contracted COVID19 at work, and subsequently brought it home to everyone in her family except her 4 year old brother. Thankfully everyone is now okay, but the waiting period to get to that point was absolutely awful. Watching an entire family, already scrutinized for the color of their skin, navigate and cope with being infected with this awful disease was absolutely heart breaking. Access to healthcare is not universal, and it could not have been more prevalent than in this situation. What's worse is this entire pandemic I have been so grateful to be at my current role which I started just before, but I cannot even begin to wonder the type of chaos and fear my old co-workers have been dealing with. This was a fear realized. She had literally no support or guidance, and still doesn't, by her healthcare network as an employee infected at work.

Sonographers already spend a very long amount of time in very close proximity to patients, having to touch them from head to toe. Most of my fellow sonographers across the country I am sure could attest to the fact that protocols have not been limited to lessen exposure time, in addition to the fact that often in radiology settings orders are placed for patients through the ED who end up testing positive shortly later, though songrpahers scan them prior without proper PPE as often the information we actually receive about patients is very limited.

I know my friend scanned multiple patients that later ended up testing as Covid19 positive.

This has made me feel hopeless, unheard, and fearfu
OE_positive:
So many of my friends and loved ones have made an effort to thank me for the work that I am doing. I am very lucky to have friends that live all over the world, and to receive little care packages form people I miss regardless has been very encouraging and uplifting. I have felt immense love.

But with such love comes also loneliness. As a person who lives alone, this has been incredibly isolating. I want to see and hug these people. That is very, very hard.
OE_other:
Hanging a banner over the entrance that says, "Welcome Heroes", is not enough to keep us motivated as we risk our lives and the lives of or families to fight this pandemic. I can speak for many healthcare workers when I say I love what I do and I do it because I want to help people. But make no mistake that majority of us are also doing this to pay our bills, to put roofs over our heads, and to provide for our children.

The way that the system has been manipulating PTO etc, it's alarming. Paying me is how I feel appreciated by my entity. I feel fulfilled on my own pandemic or not that's why I am here.

OE_upsetting: The one thing causing the most aggravation is trying to manage doing schoolwork at home with my kids, keep taking care of my family and house, and also work on top of that. I am also pregnant which has not been pleasant especially during all of this. I also am frustrated with the media, I don't know what is true or not true and/ or who to believe.
OE_positive: I feel that people are in general very appreciative for all of those working on the front lines and are realizing who/what is really important in this world. I hope that after this is over we are all a little kinder and more appreciative.
OE_other: I was also pregnant during all of this which made things a little more complicated... some of these questions might apply differently if I were not pregnant (such as drinking... I do drink occasionally when not pregnant but currently not drinking at all due to pregnancy.) Overall, it did feel pretty terrifying at first but as time has gone on and things have settled a bit I have also felt a little better about working in the hospital.

OE_upsetting: The end of my maternity leave overlapped with the start of the pandemic. Not being able to see my parents and use them as a pop-off valve for childcare has definitely made me feel sad and overwhelmed.
OE_positive: Because we have all been sheltering in place, I have gotten to know our au pair much better and been spending more time with her and talking with her.

OE_upsetting: the amount of people and effected all ages.
OE_positive: reconnecting with nurses I used to work with virtually.

OE_upsetting: The hard part when I'm at work is when sick patient's get dropped off by family members and they aren't allowed visitors. Pt and visitor get very upset but realize why. The other upsetting factor is watching someone die alone. The social isolation is getting "real old" and that is the hardest part of this whole pandemic for me. It's not the same talking to family/friends on Zoom...etc.
OE_positive: I believe nurses etc have always been appreciated on some level. But the outpouring from friends and family that are concerned about me and appreciation seems to have been elevated to another level.

OE_upsetting: seeing patients die alone- no one should have to die alone
OE_positive: going camping in central PA- I forgot about the pandemic for a few days

OE_upsetting: Can't think of one - I've been lucky
OE_positive: Great to see everyone pitching in for the response

OE_upsetting: A friend of my partner's committed suicide during the pandemic. I didn't know him, but I feel sad for my partner and scared that others will struggle with their mental health during this time.
OE_positive: Getting together with friends online more frequently- talking to people that I hadn't talked to much before this happened. It has been nice to re-connect with some old friends. It has made me feel more connected to people across the country, though I don't feel I have been connecting with people in my own city.
OE_other: I am working with patients remotely providing therapy over the phone or over video. The experience is interesting because I'm struggling with my own mental health and response to the pandemic as well. At times I feel I am really connecting with people, and other times I feel more isolated and sad because of what people are going through. It's a really interesting time to be working in the healthcare field. I hope we all make it through ok!

OE_upsetting: Having people tell my children they are not welcome at their house for risk of infection
OE_positive: Watching the support for first responders
OE_other: it is disheartening to hear that the administration bonuses are not being eliminated but our merit raises are

OE_upsetting: Hearing about death and seeing loss of employement
OE_positive: Being around family

OE_upsetting: Friends and relatives sharing conspiracy nonsense on social media - angry, frustrated, and annoyed.
OE_positive: Family has not gotten it. Made me feel hopful.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Unable to apply for or find a job, and I’m about to graduate residency so not sure what I’m doing next year.
OE_positive: Got some extra money

OE_upsetting: I lost a family member and was unable to travel to support my family through the process. I have been away from my family and children for 8 weeks to avoid infecting them and have missed major at home events.
OE_positive: Hazard pay and acknowledgement of the costs the pandemic has placed on us

OE_upsetting: Initially told that neither providers nor patients needed masks for routine interactions. Felt it was wrong and made me angry and let down
OE_positive: Proud of response of nurses and doctors, my colleagues
OE_other: The pressures and worry due to financial losses are immense.

OE_upsetting: Being away from my kids...not being able to hug them. It hurts not to be there for them
OE_positive: Seeing people come together across the world over this. When I am home, isolating with my family if a gift. Eating out much less than we used to, eating healthier.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Parents and patients frequently do not tell us in triage when we ask - whether they are  Covid + or a PUI-- but then when they get to the room, they confess.  several nurses have come  back to me, accusing me of not properly doing my job and protecting them from risk of exposure.  I don't have any way to get parents/patients to be more forthcoming with information.  But it makes me feel awful and fearful that I would somehow be responsible for a co-worker becoming exposed because I did not do my job right.
OE_positive: I spend more time with my teenagers at home

OE_upsetting:
Two equally upsetting events:
1) A covid patient of mine in the ICU quickly began decompensating to extremis and I was told not to enter the room (the fellow entered, but as a resident I was to stay outside), the nurse pulled the curtain and I was forced to stand on tables to see what was happening with my patient. I felt completely helpless, worthless, and full of hopeless anxiety. I felt that I had no skills to provide to the situation. I had no value. Zero. Even for the most menial of things. We decided to administer stress dose steroids, there was no nurse around me except the one inside the room, and I can't override medications in the pixis, so I just paced back and forth looking for a nurse to pull the medications. Completely useless while my patient was in extremis. One of the worst feelings of my residency. A completely different feeling than earlier years when maybe I didnt have the knowledge to help a patient in extremis.. This, I just had no value. 

2) A covid patient of mine in the ICU who had been successfully extubated, and was felt to be improving, began slowly decompensating over about 3 days with increased oxygen requirements, secretions that were difficult to manage, and an impossibly weak cough after being intubated for 3 weeks. But the hospital policy was to not allow deep suctioning of covid patients. I spent 48hrs talking to everyone I could find--respiratory therapists, nurse managers, attendings, other residents--to see what work around there was because if we didnt start suctioning, he was going to develop a mucus plug and die suddenly. The exact same scenario happened with another of my covid patients who wasnt able to be suctioned after extubation and we watched him die. I didnt want that to happen again. I couldnt watch another patient die because of a strict restriction on simple life saving techniques like suctioning. But, the system beat me, and after 48hrs of fighting the system and trying to find an alternative, it was clear that I
OE_positive: I'm not sure.

OE_upsetting: I'm Chinese American and felt awkward when I was in the middle of a conversation between attendings that were teasing Traditional Chinese Medicine and started making fun of the wild animal trade. Although I obviously don't support the wild animal trade, there was definitely a racial component to their discussion and a real "us vs. them" vibe.
OE_positive: I've turned to a vegetarian, minimalist, eco-friendly lifestyle that makes me feel more grounded in nature. I sometimes think of my time visiting Buddhist temples and take more time for self-reflection.

OE_upsetting: patients delaying other care for fear of coming to the hospital.
OE_positive: probably improved my relationships at home.
OE_other: impressed with the management teams response. I'm concerned about how long the transition to whatever normal is will be

OE_upsetting: Prefer not to say
OE_positive: Spending more time with family and having time to try new hobbies like cooking and gardening

OE_upsetting: Watching patients die in the ICU without family able to visit both COVID positive and negative patients.  Please note during the survey as volunteer night intensivist, new stressors are normal as well as sleeping issues and shifting from normal to night to normal duties as well as appropriately being concerned for critically ill patients.
OE_positive: I see my young children and get more hugs than I have in years.
OE_other: I felt better when I was able to do what I love to do, which is take care of patients. The greatest level of stress has come from deferring treatment from my cancer patients and not being able to tell them when they could get needed surgeries.  Many patients' stress was transferred to myself and my staff with much of the uncertainty.  Volunteering has impacted my ability to get research done as I have to reset to daytime hours after doing 3 weekend nights in a row

OE_upsetting: Learning about people I know losing people to COVID-19. Hearing about people separated from their families to treat COVID-19 patients. Makes me feel sad and a little worried about my own family.
OE_positive: More family time. More time for non-clinical work. More quiet time. Overall, more relaxed.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: I have witnessed very poor PPE use in the hospital by employees when not working with patients. Any attempt to remind people to use PPE around each other and/or to social distance at work has been met with hostility. I feel powerless to do anything to make a safer working environment.
OE_positive: I have had several very positive experiences with neighbors and coworkers that I usually do not get along with, focused on protecting our workplace and community from COVID-19
OE_other: Hospitals have not escaped the political polarization of the country. Whether an administrative group (hospital-wide, departmental, or other) strongly enforces protective strategies or not, and whether they have a more hierarchical/individualistic vs Kaizen/just culture view of employee roles is inconsistent throughout the hospital.

OE_upsetting: Not being able to complete phone visits. While other providers can, my colleagues and I cannot due to billing issues. This has made me feel unsupported by my hospital system, unappreciated, and unnecessary.
OE_positive: Our division director sends out daily updates that make me feel more connected with my work community.

OE_upsetting: we discovered I was pregnant Feb 29th before the pandemic hit. Exploring our options and navigating a pregnancy through a pandemic is hard, especially when you have to go to your appointments alone and not receive the care you need through a virtual appointment.
OE_positive: I have become closer to my family, checking in on our grandparents
OE_other: We are truly all in this together and navigating this pandemic as a whole.

OE_upsetting: A comment made by significant other that, something will kill him, maybe this. I know that we all will parish at some point, but comments like this just tick me off.
OE_positive: Co-workers who have always had a positive thought or a funny meme to get through the day.

OE_upsetting: Being told we will not be given n95 masks to see COVID patients in the hospital
People close to me have died
OE_positive: None
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Housemate rushed to the hospital at 2am with suspected symptoms. We had to deep clean at home and he got tested. Tested negative. But put us all on edge and one housemate left to live elsewhere.
OE_positive: Seeing all the encouraging signs on the freeway and in neighborhoods. Seeing people outside walking and playing. Seeing acts of solidarity. It makes me happy and cry a little.

OE_upsetting: The department where I previously worked (I transitioned to a new job/department during the pandemic) did nothing to minimize exposure.  That is, until someone in the department was infected.  It upset me that leadership knew we were vulnerable as it is a call center setting and no moves were being made.  Minimal communication was being relayed about what was being done in preparation, what options we, as employees, had, we were told we absolutely needed to be at work regardless of how we were feeling towards our safety during the pandemic because we are vital to the business.  Again, it took a couple of people being infected and enough employees to stand up and say, "What are YOU doing to keep us safe?" before changes were made.  Weeks went by.  It was like President Trump knowing about this virus, knowing it was coming, but doing nothing to prepare for the inevitable.  Ludacris.
OE_positive: With starting at my new jobs, I have had much more flexibility, have felt full support, have felt like leadership within the new department genuinely cares about the safety of its staff and its patients.  I have been fortunate to work from home as my two children have not been in school and I am not able to afford alternate care for them.
OE_other: I am proud of leadership within UIHC as an organization with the swift action that was taken, although lots of kinks needed to be worked out.  This is like nothing any of us have ever experienced, so working out details and trial/error are to be expected.  The PPE delegation and distribution was appropriate and shifts in what our engineering department manufactured to help with PPE shortages should be applauded.

OE_upsetting:
Childcare has been an issue. My mom lives out of state, my dad is deceased. My husband's parents are local and sometimes watch my children. We are both essential workers. 

We started seeing my husband's parents and my niece and nephew after about 7 weeks of isolating with just us and our two preschool aged kids.

 Today, my in-laws allowed another one of their grandkids over, my niece, who had traveled out of state from Pennsylvania to South Carolina for a road trip for a few days, out of state. Like she got out of the car after driving to South Carolina for a week and was dropped off at my in-laws house/her grandparents house like it's no big deal the entire nation is still locked down and no one is back at school or work.

And then no one, including my spouse who is on a national covid committee at his place of employment for a Fortune 500 company, could understand why I was making such a big deal out of the fact that my niece had been with all these new adults and no one was isolating themselves. She hugged my child and then everyone made me out to be a monster because I said my niece should not be in the house because of COVID. And they all just said "oh well, she isn't sick, she's not like coughing or has a runny nose."
OE_positive: more pride for essential workers nationwide; many essential workers are female, etc
OE_other:
Overall *working* the during COVID-19 pandemic has been a positive experience, and I mostly feel safe at work. We only wear a surgical mask and goggles in our ED; N95s are not required and only encouraged for aerosolizing procedures. 

I feel anxiety primarily because when I am not at work, I'm home with two small children and I can't go anywhere; I can't take them to play anywhere, no one else can watch them, and my husband works full time and has been back at his office for two weeks. I work full time night shift. The childcare situation is abysmal; I had to pay for their private preschool tuition IN FULL, and am now paying for my babysitter to come the day after I have work because there is no school. We earned too much money to receive any government assistance related to the pandemic. Everything feels like complete bullshit. Thanks for the free pizza. Bust mostly, thank God I found an old bottle of Lexapro. Namaste. Thank you for coming to my TED Talk.

OE_upsetting: Nothing too upsetting. I had to postpone my wedding, which stinks. Not too happy about that.
OE_positive: I've had some more time off than I am used to! So I have been able to spend more time with my fiancee.
OE_other: Honestly it doesn't really feel like residency to me. I have too relaxed of a schedule. I want to get back to operating. I am more negatively impacted by self quarantine at home than I am by any changes at work.

OE_positive: appreciation
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Can't think of anything significant.

OE_upsetting: I led a trauma resuscitation of a 5 year old boy and while we were all properly PPE'd I feel that all the thought and prep that goes into making sure we're all safe and minimizing personnel exposure, we may be sacrificing the same quality of preparation and care that would normally be given to a critically ill or injured child. We lost pulses on the child almost immediately upon arrival to the our trauma bay and we attempted to resuscitate him for almost an hour until his father arrived and then we stopped resuscitative efforts. The communication between staff in the bay and our newly formed command center is difficult due to masks and face shields and some in PAPR.
OE_positive: The ability to reconnect virtually with friends from high school, college who don't live close by has been great. Also, seeing family members who live in other countries has been wonderful as well.

OE_upsetting: Inability to continue my clinical practice as it was prior to the pandemic.
OE_positive: Being able to spend a lot of time with my family and seeing how wonderful they all are!

OE_upsetting: My daughter's college graduation being canceled and having to cancel two trips to California (one for her graduation, another for pleasure).  I am saddened for my daughter and stressed about her trying to find a job. All 3 of my kids are in college (2 in CA and one in NH - the one in NH came home), so it's been stressful helping them navigate this term online.  It's been difficult for my son, who is home from NH, to not be on campus (to complete his freshman year).  He's working really hard to the point that I think it's unhealthy.  I wish he felt like he could relax a bit and get more exercise.  He's in college, so I'm trying to let him navigate this term and not be an overbearing mother but it's hard feeling like all he does is study and interacts with us mainly just to eat dinner.
OE_positive: I've been able to get more caught up on my clinical work (calling patients with labs, notes, etc).  I've been more cognizant of trying to relax - going for longer walks with the dog, reading more for pleasure, watching TV with my husband, cooking more/trying new recipes.  Basically, trying to "smell the roses" more.
OE_other: This survey is a little hard to fill out because I have been working from home since March.  I am currently helping remotely with the Family Connect program, to communicate with families of COVID-19 inpatients, but the questions imply I'm working IN the hospital.  I also couldn't specify that I have 3 children, all college-age, who were away when this started but then 1 child is now home due to the pandemic (i.e. it was hard to answer what my living situation is "normally" since with college-age kids, it varies depending on their schedule - they are in and out of the house at different times of the year).

OE_upsetting: Feeling disconnected from friends and family.
OE_positive: The support from the community for being a healthcare provider.

OE_upsetting: Delaying of shutdown and early opening of the state. Felt no control.
OE_positive: Patients are eating more at home and hence better BP and less edema.

OE_upsetting: Having a colleague and friend as a patient and admitting him to the ICU. We are similar in age, hobbies, healthy lifestyles  and life responsibilities. It made me feel sad, angry and scared on how this could happen to all of us.
OE_positive: I've enjoyed the love and support from my friends, family, church, coworkers and employer. I've been blessed receive several phone calls, care packages, letters to myself and family throughout this pandemic. In the beginning I wasn't expecting any of it and truthfully did not know how to react.  But since then it has given me hope in humanity and clarity on why we are here is medical professionals.
OE_other: Caring and keeping contact for my aging parents has been an added variable and responsibility for myself and so many of my peers. There is fluctuating guilt you feel as a provider for the added health risk that I have for them and for my nuclear family.

OE_upsetting: Seen my college aged children loss their autonomy.    There are lots of upsetting situations at the hospital, but I have learned to process those.

OE_positive: On shifts, I have had patients thank me and when I call their family members, they have thanked me for the work I do.

OE_upsetting: Most upsetting is my feeling of needing to stay away from family and friends. I would not know how to process my feelings if I was responsible for infecting someone I cared about. OE_positive: The most positive thing that has occurred is realizing the support of friends via zoom and receipt of dinner/care packages. Unexpected kindness.

OE_upsetting: Diagnosed with COVID-19. Transmitted it to my wife and children.
OE_positive: Rotation schedule was changed such that residents were on every other week. This provided more time with my family at home, as well as more time for reading and resting.

OE_upsetting: Having patients who are seriously injured or sick and even dying who can't see their loved ones because of the hospital visitor policy. I understand the policy and certainly think it is reasonable. It's just hard to see people so alone.

I got to go on walks outside in the sun with my dog. I don't normally get to do that.
