OE_positive: Teamwork among my clinical team
OE_other: Ironically, the response to the pandemic has allowed implementation of changes in process of care that had been blocked by bureaucracy for a prolonged period of time.

OE_upsetting: Financial strain for the hospital system has created uncertainty in future employment
OE_positive: There is a lot of community support

OE_upsetting: No major upsetting events.
OE_positive: Showings of support for healthcare workers.
OE_other: No.

OE_upsetting: Not being able to get covid testing for all patients in dialysis unit that has several patients from modest socioeconomic background
OE_positive: Neighbors left gift anonymously at our house because they new we worked in the Hospital
OE_other: Nurses are amazing

OE_upsetting: My grandmother died, who lived in NYC and we were unable to have a funeral. It makes me feel sad that our family was not able to say a proper goodbye
OE_positive: Seeing a sick pediatric cardiology patient with COVID improve

OE_upsetting: having to work so much because of COVID and always having to be on call that I fell asleep at the wheel one day driving home.  It was during the day and I was on a conference call.  luckily everyone is ok and there was no accident, but I am also pregnant and was taking 3 classes at the time
OE_positive: our leadership team has gotten closer together

OE_upsetting: Nothing to think of personally. I guess as a resident with limited time off my biggest loss was that I can't travel somewhere relaxing on my vacation and having to stay home.
OE_positive: I see other colleagues and other residents ready and willing to jump in and cover different roles in the hospital or cover extra shifts to help others take days off for mental health or any other reasons. The camaraderie between our residents has been great. Our department (Anesthesia) sent extra residents (myself included) to help cover COVID MICU's and the Medicine team has been very appreciative. It makes me feel proud to be part of this medical community.
OE_other: Honestly my biggest stressor has been the politicization of the pandemic and realizing how  our medical system has grossly inadequate resources to deal with something of this magnitude. Our lack of preparation for this despite all the warnings in recent literature regarding pandemics has been embarrassing. I hope as a medical community we learn from this and do something different in preparing for the next one.

OE_upsetting: Uncertainty regarding pay changes that may happen. Increased anxiety planning for possibly needing to figure out bill/student loan payments with impending pay cuts
OE_positive: The overall community response of neighbors reaching out to each other and supporting our small business has been really touching

OE_upsetting: Financial hardship as I became the only employed adult in our home of 5 adults.
OE_positive: quality time with members of my household
OE_other: More financial support from our hospital would be nice

OE_upsetting: Not having the proper PPE concerning all patients.  Reusing masks is unacceptable but we are required to do this.
OE_positive: nothing
OE_other: I wish the leaders and companies would STOP spending money on foolish things, like thanking us or free tshirts etc.  and then 6 weeks later tell us no raises, maybe cut jobs.  STOP WASTING MONEY

OE_upsetting: Daughter and son in law developed covid-19. I was scared and concerned. Fortunately they recovered.
OE_positive: How our health system responded to the pandemic, and kept our staff informed about the rapidly changing medical landscape.

OE_upsetting: Before the pandemic was taken seriously by the government and the hospital system, we decided to cancel our wedding. The major disappointment, loss of money, then sudden surge of increased shifts at work to cover other providers who were of older age at a time when there was a major limitation on PPE was all an overwhelming start. Aside from the sadness of cancelling a wedding, feeling as if no one else took the situation seriously and feeling unprotected each time I stepped into work for the first week was disheartening.
OE_positive: When the system responded and dramatically changed the hospital policies to protect its providers, it gave hope that we would come out of this pandemic.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Losing a beloved pet during the pandemic. Due to COVID, only I could be present at the vet's office when she was put to sleep.
OE_positive: Seeing everyone come together at the hospital and support each other.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Performed chest compressions on a patient who was clinically cleared from prior covid infection without adequate PPE. Pt was later retested and found to be positive, but not until after I had gone home and potentially contaminated my household/family. By the time I was told about my exposure, it was too late to do anything to protect my household. Felt frustrated. Later, at the end of my quarantine week, I had a panic attack on the night before I had to go back to work, after very not-conscious thoughts about returning to work. ie, I didn't actively feel any particular way about going back to work, just thought, "oh it's sunday night, tomorrow I go back to work," and started having palpitations and burst into tears.
OE_positive: More time with my family, working on home projects. Feels good to cross things off the list, and have time to devote to hobbies.

OE_upsetting: Change in work environment
OE_positive: Teamwork

OE_upsetting: my significant other left me because he was afraid he would get covid from me
OE_positive: I have been able to continue to practice and see my patients thru telehealth

OE_upsetting: Having 2 people I knew from training in NYC die, made me sad.  Also my PT refused to see me citing fear they might catch it (well actually they blamed an administrator on their choice not to see healthcare providers as patients, but I found out later from their boss that was never a policy).  Makes me angry.
OE_positive: Team within the hospital feels a little tighter.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: large number of patient deaths in the outpatient dialysis unit.
OE_positive: more communication with people in my section--has been affirming
OE_other: The experience has changed.  I had a lot more anxiety and fear regarding what might happen at the beginning of the pandemic.  I have now adjusted

OE_upsetting: Go home to your country while jogging. Can't change the entire world and how people think.
OE_positive: Spent time eating dinner with family when not on house quarantine.  Everyone is usually busy with sports/school so being together is nice

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting is having patients die and not have the ability to have their families with them. It makes me feel really sad and helpless at times
OE_positive: Just seeing the “human stories” come out and also have the ability to spend more time with my family as I have the ability to work from home in some days
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: I used to spend a lot of time with my parents on a daily basis.  Since COVID-19 pandemic, I have not been able to interact in a meaningful way with my parents, who are 69 and 71 years old.  It makes me feel isolated and worried for them.
OE_positive: I like that I work from home every other week and get to spend a significant amount of time with my 3 children.  I like the feeling of togetherness during our increased family time.
OE_other: I am very happy with the way different departments have worked together to provide patient care.

OE_upsetting: My husbands ex wife didn't want my step kids in our home as I worked in the hospital, but she is an idiot.  Another upsetting was being berated by an attending for sending their patient who had new onset afib with SOB for 3 weeks to the ER (triageing them in fever clinic to r/o covid).  SHe told me I sent them to the ER to catch covid and die
OE_positive: I got a message from my neighbor.  I was taking care of her father in law, we didn't know until right before he left that his son lived on my street.  The patient mentioned how he picks up his grandson and I then asked - do you have a silver care?  And he said yes.  Come to find out, he parked his car in front of my house 3 times a week to pick up his grandson and here it was, I was taking care of him.  Before I we made the connection, I was calling his wife, giving her my personal cell phone as she was so concerned that she would not be able to locate him as he navigated the hospital.  So the patient said something to his daughter in law and they think I am awesome...I kind of am
OE_other: Could be worse.  People were asked to stay home, with their loved ones, with food, shelter and electronics.  Rather this than a war with other countries

OE_upsetting: I tried to reschedule an elective schedule of patients when the CDC announced restrictions on surgery, and an administrator disallowed the cancellation or rescheduling of patients until a hospital policy was developed. It made me feel disempowered as a physician, that my medical knowledge and experience didn't matter, like a cog in faceless machine.
OE_positive: The chair of our department demonstrated advocacy and commitment to faculty health and the health of our families. I saw opportunities for physician leadership in future.

OE_upsetting: Limited ability to see family (extended)
OE_positive: A reminder of my job appreciation and care for patients.
OE_other: Not at the moment.

OE_upsetting: Concern than doctors and nursing had different instructions re: ppe . Inequity
OE_positive: Reminded me of friends I love and miss
OE_other: I think it may promote more tech in healthcare

OE_upsetting: I recently got married in February 2020 and have not been able to meet my wife since the wedding as she’s a medical resident in Miami.
OE_positive: A lot of my patients are considered high risk patients and although I was initially bracing for a lot of causalties, a lot of my patients actually pulled through unscathed and I feel happy for them. Moreover, my team at work planned these couple of months exceptionally well and were an efficient unit while social distancing at work or working from home.
OE_other: It’s been a long tiring couple of months. I think everyone who works in the hospital - from the physicians to the cafeteria workers, from nurses to EVS, everyone has put their best foot forward.

OE_upsetting: Working in the ICU, and was being verbally mistreated my a few nurses and even my attending. Since my duties as a resident have become different taking care of COVID patients rather than non-COVID patients, it already made my meaningless-feeling work feel even more meaningless.
OE_positive: Seeing a discharged COVID patient reunite with their family - it's not something we get to see when working in the ICU. Helped to remind me that recoveries do happen, and our long days in the MICU are not meaningless.

OE_upsetting: I've had an old high school buddy who is currently in a medical field regularly share false information on COVID-19 and after correcting him he unfriended me on social media.
OE_positive: A few in my family have been making cloth masks regularly and supplied my wife and I with plenty of them.
OE_other: As someone who doesn't work directly with COVID-19 patients, it's been a strange experience. My coworkers and I were reassigned to COVID-19 related duties while our lab was shut down for about a month. I see the numbers and reports regularly reported by the hospital but I don't encounter it personally, though I know it's having dramatic, devastating effects. It's a silent war that doesn't hit home until it eventually does, and that's made it difficult to convey how important precautions are to some of the public.

OE_upsetting: I developed an upper respiratory/ sinus infection and feared I had contracted Covid.
OE_positive: I was released from working inpatient RN on Covid floor and was able to return to my normal position as ambulatory nurse coordinator.

OE_upsetting: My daughter was unable to finish her senior year of college on campus or say goodbye to her professors/friends. It feels helpless there is nothing I can do to replace the all the "senior" traditions she missed out on.
OE_positive: When working from home, I had more time at home to declutter and prepare to move. This was a silver lining and a relief.
OE_other: I am extremely grateful to still be earning a paycheck and not burdened with extra financial concerns.

OE_upsetting: The attending doctor and I were discussing stopping chemotherapy treatment and end of life care. It was hard not to hold his hand and hug him. We actually did end up hugging at the end of the conversation.
OE_positive: More quality time with my family
OE_other: I think the telemedicine is very effective and useful!

OE_upsetting: Governor Kemp misinforming the public with deliberately misleading numbers about infection and death rates, and reopening the state without instituting adequate safety measures (such as requiring people to wear masks when in public). This angers and frustrates me, and makes me worry about the coming months.
OE_positive: Family and friends have reached out to me to check on me and offer support. Even people that I don't communicate with often have thought of me and contacted me. It's heart-warming to know that people care.

OE_upsetting: My aunt and uncle's house burnt to the ground and were left with nothing.  It makes me feel more sad about the world and why did it have to happen to them.
OE_positive: I was able to spend more time with my kids and spend time in my house.  Usually with all the kids' sports we were always running from one thing to the next.  Now we have time to have family dinners and enjoy each other's company.  It makes me feel happy to do this.
OE_other: The physical strain from our job is usually the exhausting part but since Covid, I feel like the mental and emotional strain has surpassed the physical strain.  I always worry that we are going to miss something and it will harm a patient and or a fellow employee.

Other than a short (~ 1 week) slow down in April, I have been working my regular job and it's been busy (ortho trauma) so many days with long hours.  What's uncertain is much of the financial implications as a result of the hospital financial problems.  So, despite working regularly, there is a high chance of a decreased income which brings up conflicting feelings.  On one hand, grateful to be working and employed.  On the other, the exposure and risk of going to the hospital each day is uncompensated.  Standing in an operating room with assistants extremely close in regular surgical masks for hours at at time does increase exposure -- I have to hope each day that none of them are ill or carriers and expose me.

OE_upsetting: Death of a friend. Terrible loss.
OE_positive: impressed by hospital system collaboration.  And  University response has been present.
OE_other: I am outpatient only

OE_upsetting: My son's college graduation was cancelled and his post-college job was eliminated
OE_positive: Our clinical team's ability to shift work flows to accommodate our patients.

OE_upsetting: Being separated from family. It creates more sadness, isolation, and fatigue given the support that my family provides.
OE_positive: Enjoying seeing my children in between patients and having my hours be a little more flexible

OE_upsetting: The potential threat of being RIF'd from my job and/or knowing that others in my department will lose their job as a result of the University needing to save/cut finances.
OE_positive: My mental health has significantly improved. I am able to work from home and feel more content, at peace, relaxed, and more focused on my work as a result. I recognize that I am one of the few and lucky. Also, I have no fear of becoming infected and/or getting sick. I am also not afraid of dying, so I may not be a great representation of how this pandemic has affected my work-life balance.
OE_other: I am working from home and have not been into the clinic/hospital in 2 months.

OE_upsetting: Another team member being allowed to go part-time after she essentially said she was quitting if not allowed (and due to the hiring freeze, twisted arms to get her way) despite me asking to go (less) part-time due to severe post-partum depression and PTSD.
OE_positive: Getting to know my team ever better due to some fun things we have started doing (virtual game nights, a thing called COVID Silver Linings - random questions about ourselves/lives)
My boyfriend and I both still have our jobs. It is a thing we remind ourselves to be grateful for every single day.
OE_other: I started my job in the middle of the pandemic. Luckily, admin was given the approval to work from home, so I had to navigate through the difficult transition of training for a new job virtually

OE_upsetting: Had to close my small business due to local government making it impossible to continue.
OE_positive: nothing really.

OE_upsetting: Initially I had some difficulty convincing family members about the severity of the pandemic and the need to stay home. Had a lot of anxiety about them getting sick and my own health conditions putting me at increased risk for mortality.
OE_positive: Have been able to do more virtual patient care and become more productive working from home (pre-pandemic I was unable to get much done if wfh).

OE_upsetting: Seeing people who don't take the pandemic seriously. It is somewhat angering.
OE_positive: Seeing colleagues come together and support each other. Makes me feel happy and lucky to have my job.
OE_other: Not at this time.

OE_upsetting: Not being able to be with family in person, to have my children play with their cousins and grandparents.
OE_positive: Feeling more connected with my colleauges as we're in this together.

OE_upsetting: Lack of recognition by his for work done by my group
OE_positive: My department is now cohesive
OE_other: It's a privilege

OE_upsetting: Our residency program completely revamped our rotation schedules during this COVID pandemic, so I missed out on 2 of the most highly-raved-about rotations in our program. Everyone has had to make compromises through this pandemic (some people in our residency lost their vacation), but this made me feel helpless (loss of control) and very unlucky.
OE_positive: Stimulus checks + hospital bonus, freebies from companies thanking the “frontline heroes,” lessened workload

OE_upsetting: Having a patient with a tracheostomy who admitted prior to Covid and  was supposed to be in non Covid area of the hospital when masks were being reserved and not being used for non Covid patients and patients that would have previously qualified to wear PPE. Patient  become symptomatic and test positive for Covid. Had been caring for her for several weeks.  Had suctioned teach on multiple occasions without any PPE and then with face shield and no mask for about a week. Had reassured patient that she was at low risk because she was hospitalized before Covid was in state.  Apparently transmitted by a OT working w patient.  Caused concern for the patient who had multiple other medical issues, the other staff on the unit, and I was concerned that I could have been infected and transmitted it to my husband, and college age son now at home and adult daughter who is in same home. I was very concerned for all, angry that we did not have proper PPE w aerosolized exposure and very afraid I would transmit it to my family.  I also was very annoyed that there was so much news focused on how terrible it was for people to have to stay home when I and my coworkers were had to go to work and be exposed all while being expected to act like we thrived on our sacrifice.  And then heard news stories about how construction workers often had to lift 2 ends of a piece of equipment which put them at great risk!  And now waiting for the hospital to decide how much of a pay cut they will be doing to offset the cost of losing money during Covid.  But good news they continued to pay everyone who was not required to work for weeks and sacrificed by staying home.(sarcastic statement) Feeling like we should all be able to eat but if we are the ones to be put at risk and keep working we should not then be punished to support those who were not.
OE_positive: My son came home for spring break and did not go back to college but stayed with us.  Nice to have him home!
OE_other: I think as a county and as a medical system (?) we should have been prepared for this. It has been known for years this would happen. I hope that once we get through this we will be more prepared for future problems. I also hope we will decide to restructure our entire health care system to treat all. We need to stop wasting so much money on people trying to beg insurance companies to cover things patients need. And stop having more people reading documentation to make sure it phrased correctly for insurance reimbursement than we have actually trying to take care of patients.

OE_upsetting: Being 36+ weeks pregnant in a covid only unit and not being moved to another unit.in the hospital. I was disappointed in my management team not reaching out to other units to see if I could move for the last few weeks of my pregnancy.
OE_positive: No one I work with has contracted the virus!! Means we must be doing something right and some of our sickest patients are getting better and having positive outcomes! Its makes me feel like we are making a difference
OE_other: It's a scary time but my work unit is a great team and we all work together for better patient care and outcomes despite it all!

OE_upsetting: Seeing so many people dying on TV. I'm in pediatrics so we see less but there is still a constant worry that I could bring it home to may family. I worry so much about my immunocompromised parents. I actually have to say I feel safest at work with all my PPE then I do at the store.
OE_positive: I have been able to save money and pay off bills. I have also been able to spend well needed quality time with my family. It has been a nice reset from lifes crazy.
OE_other: I am thankful and blessed for my God given Vocation as a Nurse. I am blessed for the best Quaran-Team a person could ask for in a hospital. I am proud to be a nurse and Proud to be able to be on the front lines during this pandemic.

OE_upsetting: Not able to see family and friends - makes me feel sad
OE_positive: We made a home gym
OE_other: Nothing further

OE_upsetting: My child not being able to see her grandparents and the fear that she will not know/recognize them when restrictions begin to ease
OE_positive: The sense of camaraderie amongst all hospital staff (physicians, nurses, ancillary staff, etc.)

OE_upsetting: I am very close to my family and they are a large part of my support system. It was very hard for me to deal with the increased stress of work and have less outlets and positive interactions with friends and family. Also worrying about older family members contacting COVID.
OE_positive: All the love and support from coworkers and the community. My relationship with my partner has also growth stronger and feel like if we can be loving and supportive during this hard and stressful time with can get through a lot. I have also been VERY involved in my garden and it has been an outlet for me because I don't have to socially distance from them. :)
OE_other: Not having enough N95s was the biggest issue at my hospital.

OE_upsetting: Having to isolate myself and our toddler from my husband as he is a HCW as well and was exposed to coronavirus, knowing that he may become positive and would not be able to attend the birth of our second child. It was a stressful, anxiety-filled time until the test came back negative.
OE_positive: Seeing the resilience of the patients and parents that I help to care for and realizing that everyone is becoming more attuned to mental and behavioral health problems and the impact is has on your wellbeing.

OE_upsetting:
I have felt marginalized- not
Included in discussion and my suggestion s are ignored
OE_positive: Some Efforts by leadership to move quickly
OE_other: Missing the patients in person...something is missing.

OE_upsetting: I had to cancel my wedding. I feel depressed and sad. I also have no job lined up for when fellowship ends in 6 weeks. After 10 years of medical training, I feel lost and hopeless.
OE_positive: Decrease in patient volume temporarily made daily work less time-pressured

OE_upsetting: Attempting to homeschool my son and work from home too. Very stressful
OE_positive: Not making my hour and a half commute to and from work. Less road rage

OE_upsetting: I have not felt unsafe or upset.  I was reduced in hours from 40 to 24, which I had to accommodate to.  I understood the reasoning.
OE_positive: I work for Emory, and their confident and reassuring manner in which they handled this pandemic has kept their workers positive and hopeful.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Decreased hours, financial insecurity due to impending furloughs and ending contributions to retirement plan.
OE_positive: I have always been very conscious of cleaning before and after patients and in common areas but not all of my coworkers do the same but since COVID, we are all cleaning and are conscientious of keeping the patients and employees safe.

OE_upsetting: I think the lack of government response to the pandemic.

Only one thing happened at work in which I was asked to do an assignment which was asked of me and was unable to complete because it was too much in a short time. I felt management was not considerate in know that the task could have not been completed on time because of the magnitude of the project assigned to only one person with limited recourses.
OE_positive: Being able to keep my job even though at first it was working for 3 days. Hoping that I continue to have a job.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: Learning from a person that they have lost loved ones to the virus. upsetting, empathy
OE_positive: Moving from a horrible rental into a new built home. Better
OE_other: No thank you

OE_upsetting: I am unable to see my 2 grandchildren for fear of infecting them.  I have a new granddaughter and I cannot hold her.  Do not know if and when this will be safe.  This is very depressing.
OE_positive: I feel that the health care delivery in the United States is finally getting attention.  Perhaps this will be an incentive to improve health care coverage and delivery to those who need it.
OE_other: There is nothing that I would rather do with my life than to be a physician.

OE_upsetting: Ultimately my great concern that if I were exposed at work and were asymptomatic and contagious, that I could infect someone else.
OE_positive:
The spirit of working together to help others and to sacrifice to help others and to share these thoughts and among our team has been gratifying.  We are all in healthcare at some very significant level to help other human beings who are suffering and this desire to help others has been so present in our entire team, it has been uplifting.  It has further reinforced my vocation.

As health care providers, we do not worry so much about ourselves, but about our patients and staff and family.  That is where the stress lies.

OE_upsetting: My elderly grandparents (ages 85 and 90) live with family members who I feel are not taking precautions to prevent infection seriously enough. I worry that my grandparents will become infected and be unable to recover due to age and preexisting medical conditions.
OE_positive: When my state issues its first stay home order, I moved in with my fiance, ahead of our original schedule. This has been a wonderful change and I feel that he is incredibly supportive of me and has helped me to process my Covid-related anxiety.
OE_other: I feel that the hospital leadership and leadership within my department have done an excellent job in maintaining open and prompt communication about high-level decisions that impact all MM employees, as well as making available mental healthcare resources.

OE_upsetting: Finding out I am pregnant and not being able to secure a new OB provider without significant difficulty. Due to a history of complicated and lost pregnancies, the additional stress of unknown effects of Covid-19 on pregnancy, combined with less availability and thoroughness in services from my own healthcare providers was quite stressful.
OE_positive: Openness of my research and clinical teams to learning new Telehealth techniques

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting thing is that we were at risk of losing our jobs, it made me feel scared and hopeless
OE_positive: Being able to spend time with my loved ones that live with  me and a decrease in work flow

OE_upsetting: Restriction on making new relationships
OE_positive: Maintaining friendships (and rekindling friendships) via virtual platform. I also have taken much better care of my body through working out at home

OE_upsetting: Technical difficulties when interacting with a patient remotely.
OE_positive: I used to dread the idea of retirement, now, not so much

OE_upsetting: I don't have anything that negative to put into words.  I don't like wearing the masks, but I do, they are just uncomfortable and very hot.  However, I try to put myself in all the shoes of the people that have to wear them all day, every day. Thank you to all the front line workers!!!
OE_positive: I feel my work/life balance is better.  I usually have about 2.5 to 3 hours commute time per day, and been working from home and love that.  My job however, has not been as rewarding, as I am doing mostly rescheduling and revamping the grids.

OE_upsetting: Not related to COVID but my hometown flooded due to failure of two dams north of the town (Midland MI).
OE_positive: Spending more time with my daughter and our puppy. Engaging in more outside activities (chalk art, walks, bubbles, hikes).

OE_upsetting: The constant feeling that nothing is getting 100% of my time.  My kids don't get my undivided attention, my work is passable, but not outstanding like it usually is, my house is a disaster, and I"m on edge all the time.  I end up working into the evening and weekends now when I didn't before because its impossible to do it all from home everyday in an 8-hour day.  The contanst feeling like a failure in all areas is the most upsetting part.
OE_positive: In many ways, life seem simpler.  No more running around all evening for activities, more focused time at home (when work allows) has been nice.  Its been amazing to not have to wake up on a schedule and start our day off wrong because mornings are always rough.  Now we just gradually start our day on our own time and its been such a blessing!  Also, less money on dining out, gas, etc has been helpful.  Finally, my kids are so excited to cook and bake every day!  They will be amazing when this is over and I'll not have to cook anymore!

OE_upsetting: Grandmother passed away. Timing of things was horrible. Not being able to see her or hold funeral. Couldn't even go to a florist. Plus the added stress of work and everything else going on. Added extra stress, frustration, and sadness.
OE_positive: Honestly just seeing numbers of new cases going down.
OE_other: There needs to be hazard pay for those on the frontlines.

OE_upsetting: Worries about losing my job and my daughters senior high school year / upcoming college experience/ decisions
OE_positive: closer with family
OE_other: I have been actively engaged in support teams throughout the hospital

OE_upsetting: The unknown. Not knowing when we can get back to a more normal life, if ever.
OE_positive: Spending quality time with family.

OE_upsetting: I am not in direct contact with patients. The most upsetting thing related to covid is my University's economic response. There have been significant furloughs and reduction in benefits which is stressful.
OE_positive: skip

OE_upsetting: Knowing that my family still has to go to work and put themselves at risk. My dad who has 6 stents went on unemployment but his boss asked him to come in to help with work, knowing he has heart problems. My dads place of work is within a part of Michigan with a high COVID-19 positive cases. I can't protect him, he is sturbborn and a hard worker, but this is unacceptable.
OE_positive: Being allowed to work from home and knowing my fiance, who is Type 1 diabetic, has been working from home since the start of COVID-19
OE_other: When it's time to reopen I worry most about the people who don't take this serious and their actions

OE_positive: telehealth for vulnerable patients

OE_upsetting: My parents who live in a different state than myself have not been consistently following COVID precautions, such as wearing masks at work, despite their increased risk (e.g., cardiovascular risk factors, smoking), which has increased my anxiety.
OE_positive: I have had to transition away from my typical clinical duties due to COVID precautions, which has allowed me to dedicate more time to my research efforts.
OE_other: N/A

OE_upsetting: Having to stop research activities associated with in-person human subjects research.  I have had to find ways to keep my research program going and my team employed/funded and busy with remote work.  I feel responsible for their financial and emotional well being during this time, it's upsetting to see them struggling with what's going on, and I don't feel as effective in helping those around me as I usually do.  Having to pause the bulk of my research and the uncertainty around timelines, funding, etc. has made me concerned about my ability to be productive enough to obtain tenure in the next few years.
OE_positive: Friends and family reaching out to provide support.  Many people in my life are coming together in a positive way.  It makes me hopeful and I am glad to know that I'm not struggling with this alone.
OE_other: I think it's important to note that my duties are primarily research-based (85% research), so I have not been physically working in the hospital since the pandemic.  My current research duties are focused on analyzing data, writing papers and grants. I carry a small outpatient clinic load and do some teaching, which is all now being done remotely.

OE_upsetting: shutting down our lab and not being able to finish experiments.
OE_positive: our community is more friendly
OE_other: not everyone is following the guidelines. and the bathrooms have been so much cleaner.. thank you.

OE_upsetting: Being quarantined, not knowing how this stuff is spread. Afraid to go places, thinking other people are not so careful.  Knowing people that are passing away.
OE_positive: That my family in my household is ok.
OE_other: None

OE_upsetting: As the DIO at Emory, it is upsetting when trainees are COVID positive or have had significant emotional challenges.  I wish that I could do more to help.
OE_positive: More time with my family,  more time to relax, less travel, less chaos, more casual dress code.  Overall feeling more relaxed.

OE_upsetting: Watching others disregard the restrictions or distancing measures, not wearing masks, not social distancing, gathering, protesting, etc.

OE_upsetting: Frustrated by my internet connection resulting in not being able to work from home
OE_positive: Feel closer to immediate family and have spent more relaxed time around them because of the shelter at home

OE_upsetting: My supervisor has consistently discussed furloughs and layoffs (RIFs) since day one even though that was not the hospital guidance at all.  8 weeks later, the hospital is moving towards that but it has felt punitive and difficult from day one.
OE_positive: My hospital has actually been great and it is been helpful.  Daily a message was released about COVID+ numbers and discharges, they have given time for working parents to parent their children (who are now home) and they just released a training to get people back to work that included information on wearing masks, one-way hallways, etc.  It has been positive and science driven
OE_other: At the beginning of the pandemic, I desperately wanted to help and wanted to volunteer for the field hospital that was being established but there was not enough PPE for me to do so and feel safe (I am a Social Worker and not a doctor or nurse or RT who needed the equipment more than I did but I am also a military veteran and well trained for situations such as these).  This frustration of not being able to help people when I am trained to do so has lingered longer than expected.  I feel I may never get over feeling like I failed people who needed me because I couldn't be guaranteed safety for myself and family when I came home from work.

OE_upsetting: - having friends and family that are sick due to COVID-19. I feel sorry for them and I try my best to support them but it hard given the current restrictions.
OE_positive: seeing people get better. slowing down a bit.

OE_upsetting: We couldn't contact a friend of ours, who was quite sick and was told not to come to the hospital. My husband had to go to his home and get an update through the door. We all feel somewhat helpless.
OE_positive: Although it is a challenge, I am being allowed to work from home. One of my dogs has dementia due to old age, so I am glad I can be here for him. And my husband is great, so it is nice to see more of him.
OE_other: I am in healthcare, but not in the hospital.

OE_upsetting: The uncertainty of when our particular clinic will start seeing patients again and if anyone from our clinic will be impacted by layoffs or permanent furloughs.
OE_positive: Positive news stories about people pulling together to help and uplift others. Definitely raises your mood levels and gives you hope for the future.

OE_upsetting: Lack of support and communication from residency program administration, which was worst during the time when it appeared we may be redeployed from ambulatory clinics doing virtual work to the hospital or ICU to care for COVID patients. I felt anxious, confused, and angry.
OE_positive: Doing virtual visits from home has allowed me to see my wife and children more frequently during the week. It distracts me from my work, makes me feel more hopeful, and gives me opportunity laugh and feel joy.

OE_upsetting: Thought my spouse may have had COVID-19; very upset and anxious waiting for the results (which were negative).
OE_positive: Realized that I could be happy being at home and not working, that my identity was not just being a doctor.

OE_upsetting:
Sleep disruption, Apartment (I commute during the work week) noisy neighbors, disrupting sleep, waking up 2 to 3x/night  (M to Thurs). Manage to get 7 to 8 hours interrupted sleep. 
Seeking a different place to stay during the week.
OE_positive: Spending less on non essential items and knowing my family is staying healthy and positive.
OE_other: Our department administration and support staff have done a fine job ensuring we have what we need to do our jobs, updating us regularly about the changes, and providing the support we need. I'm grateful for the opportunity of working with a team that really cares about not only the patients but each other as well.

OE_upsetting: My aunt died after struggling with ALS for several years. It was really hard that we couldn't meet up as a family to grieve together, and it was hard to connect with cousins and other family members virtually. I felt sad, out of control, hopeless, fatigued/drained, and angry.
OE_positive: The most hopeful experience was recently, when our state allowed small groups of 10 or fewer people to meet using proper precautions (outside, masks, 6+ feet of distance, no shared food, etc.) which allowed me to see my best friends of 20+ years outdoors for a bit of time. I felt a sense of hope that things will return to "normal" eventually, and my mood lifted quite a bit as a result of this connection.
OE_other: My hospital has done a nice job overall. I feel really frustrated that the federal government is allowing any hospital to experience financial loss. My site will have to let go of 5% of employees, and will have a hiring freeze until the end of fiscal year 2021. It feels unacceptable that front line workers will lose their jobs, and that hospitals will have to shelf life-saving research projects. The federal gov should supply money to cover financial loss for medical institutions.

OE_upsetting: Anxiety related to possibility of being furloughed, having to go on unemployment, those extra benefits running out and not receiving enough money to cover my mortgage and basic needs.
OE_positive: My employer has been very supportive, trying to help us to stay gainfully employed, providing additional supports and benefits, transitioning us to be able to work from home as often as possible.  It made me feel grateful and valued.
OE_other: Just that the University of Michigan is a great health system and I am proud to work there!

OE_upsetting: My daughter needed to go to inpatient substance abuse treatment. Upon discharge the same level/availability of aftercare was not available. It makes me feel sad and helpless.
OE_positive: More time with my children that are young adults. It made me feel grateful.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: going on an elevator at work, we stopped at a floor to pick up the next people and someone looked into the elevator and said no keep going. I couldn't help but think it was because I am Asian so they didn't want to get in with me.
OE_positive: being positive through Faith.

OE_upsetting: Institutional threat to decrease size of residency program I direct to recover financial losses.  My primary response is anger at this short-sighted plan.
OE_positive: Parking is excellent.  I am pleased every morning.
OE_other: For the most part, hospital staff have been highly professional and hospital administration reasonable and transparent.

OE_upsetting: I was forced into doing video visits with patients that I was ill prepared to do.  I was never able to get training because of the backlog and felt forced into doing something I was not competent enough to do.  I fear having to take time in the future to correct mistakes or do additional work to compensate for this that will need to be done after hours.
OE_positive: I've been able to find connection and meaning through participation in my religious group via zoom meetings.

OE_upsetting: Being stir-crazy at home, which has made me feel annoyed.
OE_positive: The most positive thing has been less workdays/ less weekly duty hours in the hospital. This has made me feel happy and less burnt out!
OE_other: Obviously COVID has changed life as we know it, but the restricted duty hours have been fantastic! Also, it has been nice to be considered a "hero" by the public when we usually don't get credit.

OE_upsetting: a friend from college died in a car accident and we were not able to get together in person to remember her. isolated, sad, a magnified sense of loss of community in addition to grief.
OE_positive: increased friendships with colleagues-more personal connection, more vulnerability with each other makes me feel closer in some ways.

OE_upsetting: the idea that I might be redeployed had me frightened, but also I felt guilty when I was not deployed because I know that many providers have been working on the front lines and I feel guilty that I have not done so.
OE_positive: people helping others, reaching out and also the silver lining of having my family all under one roof for 2 months.  I loved having my 3 kids at home.

OE_positive: I have seen many displays of compassion

OE_upsetting: Having a family member die during this time. She was in the ICU and then in hospice and I was unable to be with her like I normally would have been. She was NOT sick with COVID, just to be clear. She had a stroke years ago and her overall health declined. After weeks in the hospital/hospice she passed away. It was personally difficult, heartbreaking to be away from her. It was also overwhelming to simultaneously support other family members and their grief.
OE_positive: I have enjoyed homeschooling my daughter and seeing her flourish from the one on one learning. She is advancing in many way academically as well as her creativity. The best moment was when she was received a letter from her school/teacher indicating that she would be advancing in her math course. She will be skipping 7th grade and will begin 8th grade work at the start of then next year. My daughter feels very proud of herself and her hard work. That is priceless.

OE_positive: Being part of a team to address the crisis
I wake up every day

OE_upsetting: Having COVID 19, the fear of the unknown in what was going to happen to me, how sick I was going to get, worried over getting my family ill because of me.  Until we know more, I will continue to be worried about re-infection although this worry has not impacted my ability to work.

OE_upsetting: Hospital Leadership - both administration, medicine, and nursing,  has devalued nursing by their communications and actions. Now they are cutting staffing, cutting budgets despite the fact our emergency service is seeing a surge of high acuity patients with no where to place them (long lengths of stay).  And not to mention the constant change in policies and the absolute minimum protection of PPE.  All of this is very disturbing and makes me want to leave the profession

OE_other: IT SADDENS ME THAT THE FRONTLINE WORKERS ARE DISREPECTED BY THOSE WHO CHOICE TO PROTEST FOR THEIR FREEDOM, BRINGING GUNS TO STATE CAPITALS, REFUSING TO WEAR MASK AND SOCIAL DISTANCE RULES.  THE WORST PART IS THAT TRUMP ENCOURAGES THIS BEHAVIOR.

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting thing to me is financial. Currently, workers in my clinic are facing unpaid time off because the hospital system had to cancel elective procedures. So while our administrative counterparts are working from home or collecting more in unemployment than I make exposing myself to danger each day, after the stress of working with the possibility of exposure I go home and stress over how to pay my bills. Additionally, this is hitting us just as the programs enacted to stop utility cutoffs and foreclosures are ending, since everyone else will be going back to work. So, after being asked to risk death for myself and my family, I receive no financial help during a decrease in paid working hours. I am considering leaving healthcare altogether because of this.
OE_positive: I have been communicating with my family more, which has helped stave off depression.
OE_other: As much as we have been leaned on in a time of panic, the country should now look to helping us maintain our lives and livelihood. Healthcare workers, and all "essentials" deserve an additional financial stimulus.

OE_upsetting: A weekly, if not daily, occurrence of going from a strict clinical setting (security at the door, wearing masks all day, strict PPE guidelines, and sick patients) to the outside world where people are in stores not even wearing masks. I would typically visit my parents two-three times a week and now I can't go in their house/hug them but people across Atlanta are acting like we're back to normal times.
OE_positive: Spending more time at home and focusing on myself. I was very social and busy before COVID-19, so this has weirdly felt like a needed break.
OE_other: Again, just to clarify a previous note I made regarding the "positive test" question. I did not have a COVID test but later took the antibody test which came back positive. I was home for two weeks during my time with symptoms and this time was very difficult. Not even so much from my symptoms, but from feeling alone and unimportant. Considering when I tried to get tested I was told I wasn't able to despite working in healthcare. I'm glad the shortage of tests issue is slowly being resolved but I still look towards local and national leaders. They need to do better.

OE_upsetting: Work out less. Use to go to the gym daily in am before work. Feel sluggish, lazy and a little fatigue. Now walking and riding bike at home and feel better. Not sure I did not start this earlier.
OE_positive: I am always so busy I feel like I go home to sleep. I am actually living and loving my home. I have been gardening, relaxing more and watched more Netflix movies than ever before. Unable to go out so I have transformed my home and enjoyed all the projects I have completed. Cooking more and eating healthier,
OE_other: Scary at times but I never entered the hospital in fear.

OE_upsetting: increased stress with patient care effecting everyday work and family life.  issues with the wearing a mask more--feel as if I can't breath, increased headaches because of the mask.  increased stress at work because of the schedule backlog with patients and rescheduling of procedures not just for my doctors but for doctors I don't even know.
OE_positive: I have not been able to see a light at the end of the tunnel.  I guess its good that I still had a job but I wonder if the increased stress is worth it
OE_other: this has been the most stressful thing I have had to deal with in my 25 yrs of nursing

OE_upsetting: We have been under 'stay at home' orders since March. I used to love my job, now I get anxious and panicky on the days I have to work.  It terrifies me to learn the patients I previously took care of test positive within days of my time with them.   it makes me terribly upset to see people out in public who aren't wearing masks.
OE_positive: I enjoy church services online

Thus, I feel I did not help as much as I could and that makes me feel sad and guilty.
having to listen to Trump and the people who agree with him

OE_upsetting: I am one of our medical directors and do alot of administrative work.At the beginning of the crisis the need to keep everyone safe, especially when we were not sure if we would have enough PPE, felt like a heavy burden. We worked what felt like 24x7 to get the original plans, protocols, standard work into place. The initial planning was extremely stressful. After a few weeks we fell into a routine and it was not nearly so stressful. Now there is just an underlying anxiety about work that was not there before. I believe we are all more used to it (which is both a good thing and a bad thing) but it is just right below the surface all the time now. It makes work much less pleasant than it used to be.
OE_positive: Several people in the department really stepped up during this crisis. It made me proud to be part of this department.

OE_upsetting: What has upset me the most is the overall fear of the virus and the unknown. I'm upset that my children have had interruption in their school and have had to change the way they play. I fear for my parents and other family members who are at higher-risk of complications from COVID-19.
OE_positive: I am currently doing all of my work from home, so I've been able to spend more time with my children and enjoy watching them grow and learn (both are under the age of 5). I'm hopeful that this will bring about some positive changes in the ways people do their work.

OE_upsetting: My neighbor dies of COVID. He was young and it was scary because they didn’t quarantine well. We were afraid we’d become infected as well.
OE_positive: Being able to continue research at the hospital once restrictions lifted for one of our studies which involved a outpatient procedure with hospital admission for patients with few options for treatment.

OE_upsetting: Long work hours. No specific end time when working from home. Expected to respond to emails every 15 minutes. Work life balance is overwhelming.
OE_positive: Seeing my family more! Love that we've all been home together even though I'm bogged down with work.
